report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 27-year-old woman with focal sclerosis glomerulonephritis and childhood epilepsy.  Patient seizure-free for five years.  The patient is now experiencing staring spells at work.  Previous history of tonic-clonic seizures.

MEDICATIONS: Norvasc.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz, 30 to 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Brief drowsiness is characterized by anterior spread of the alpha rhythm.  Hyperventilation does not activate the record.  The major abnormalities occur around the time of photic stimulation.  The tech starts to awaken the patient for photic.  A brief burst lasting just under one second is seen with high amplitude, sharply contoured activity without a really well-defined spike and slow wave complex, but with notched frontal activity.  Reviewing the burst with different montages, it seems to phase reverse slightly to the left.

1 seizure occurred in the EEG lab at 13:51.  This follows photic stimulation, but does not occur during photic stimulation.  The patient is resting quietly with her eyes closed.  As the seizure begins at 13:51:57, no clinical signs or symptoms are noted.  The technologist notes the change in behavior.  The patientÕs eyes open at 13:52:10.  The technologist asks the patient questions at 13:52:16.  The patient opens her eyes and swallows.  When asked where she is she replies that she is in the neurologistÕs office.  She remains somewhat confused in the minutes that follow.  The tech calls the patient at 13:52:39.   At 13:52:46, she sits, staring blankly, and then she starts to rub her eyes in her head.  The tech asks if she is okay.  At this point, when the tech is asking the patient questions, the seizure has ended and the patient is confused.

EEG characteristics of this seizure include the appearance of rhythmic theta frequency activity, which is more remarkable in the posterior regions.  This seizure seems to start with some low voltage fast activity and then some rhythmic theta, more remarkable in the posterior regions and perhaps maximum in the right posterior region.  Reviewing this seizure with a circle montage, seems to confirm a phase reversal in the right occipitotemporal region but also involving the right central region, nearly isoelectric Cz to C4.  The activity shows frequency evolution and seems to occur in two phases with secondary build-up at 13:52:19 with fast activity and more of a generalized appearance.  The activity ends at 13:52:51 as the patient starts to rub her head with postictal slowing.

HR:  96 BPM.

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Complex partial seizure, which was difficult to localize and which may have had some generalized features at the start, but with some evidence of focality in the same seizure.
2. An unusual paroxysmal burst frontal in nature.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG is diagnostic of an underlying seizure disorder.  There may be more than one contributing factor for this patientÕs seizures.  This EEG did not provide adequate localization for the seizures that this individual experienced.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Complex partial seizure, which was difficult to localize and which may have had some generalized features at the start, but with some evidence of focality in the same seizure. 2. An unusual paroxysmal burst frontal in nature.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 27-year-old woman with a childhood seizure disorder with recurrent seizures in recent months (last seizure one to two weeks ago with loss of consciousness and postictal confusion).
MEDICATIONS: Trileptal.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Previous EEGs are not available for comparison.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 10 Hz posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Brief drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements and attenuation of the alpha rhythm.  Hyperventilation produces an increase in background slowing.  Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.  Of note, there is a single four second burst in photic stimulation where the patient seems to have had eye flutter, but looking at the eyes there is no discernable eye movement, and the activity is in the frontal regions with a somewhat different field of spread in the eye monitor in comparison to the patient’s other eye movements.  This burst is highly suspicious for frontally predominant notched delta as might be seen in generalized spike and slow wave activity.
HR:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION: This EEG is abnormal due to:
1.	A single, suspicious, approximately 2 to 3 second burst of notched frontal delta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No seizures were recorded.  The activity described above can be seen in a primary or secondary generalized process.  Rather than repeating additional studies, correlation with previous studies may be the most effective way to place these findings in their appropriate clinical context.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This EEG is abnormal due to 1.A single, suspicious, approximately 2 to 3 second burst of notched frontal delta.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 27-year-old woman with childhood epilepsy with recurrent seizures – last occurring in May 2006 with loss of consciousness and postictal confusion.
MEDICATIONS: Trileptal.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record. This patient’s previous EEGs were available for comparison.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 10 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  There is a scant amount of background theta, compatible with age.  Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record producing a small amount of slowing. There is a single burst of notched slowing in the occipital regions, right greater than left, seen at the end of hyperventilation.  As the patient becomes drowsy, additional, sharply contoured irregular slowing is seen.  The burst identified is generalized, but there may be an underlying right temporal sharp wave associated with that burst.  Photic stimulation elicits scant bilateral driving.
HR:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Very subtly abnormal EEG due to:
Two somewhat unusual bursts seen in the background with some localization to the right hemisphere.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In comparison to this patient’s two previous EEGs, there is much less in the way of epileptiform activity, and the overall background is more consistently normal.  The epileptiform activity in this record was not well defined - really only suspicious underlying sharply contoured activity with the paroxysmal bursts.  These findings suggest an improvement compared to the first study.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Very subtly abnormal EEG due to Two somewhat unusual bursts seen in the background with some localization to the right hemisphere.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 63-year-old gentleman with epilepsy since the 1980s with various different seizure types including tonic-clonic and complex partial.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Phenobarbital, Keppra, Lipitor, others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 9 Hz, 30 to 50 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record producing an increase in the amplitude of the background, as well as some subtle slowing in the posterior temporal regions bilaterally. Following hyperventilation, the patient becomes drowsy with an increase in background beta activity, occasional vertex waves, and POSTS.
Photic stimulation elicits driving at intermediate and faster flash frequencies.
HR:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Very mildly abnormal EEG due to:
Posterior temporal slowing identified in hyperventilation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record.  The features described above are similar to previous EEGs, all of which have failed to identify epileptiform activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Very mildly abnormal EEG due to Posterior temporal slowing identified in hyperventilation.

report:

report:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 50-year-old female with epilepsy since 1994, but seizure-free since 1999.  Past EEG showed generalized spike and slow wave activity.
MEDICATIONS: Lamictal.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with an 11 Hz, 30 to 50 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by prominent rhythmic diffuse theta activity particularly in the occipital regions.  Hyperventilation is performed out of drowsiness and seems to accentuate this activity as well.  There are rare bursts of higher amplitude more sharply contoured frontal theta at the close of hyperventilation and there is a single, discrete left anterior temporal sharp wave in the transition from hyperventilation to sleep.  As the patient reaches stage I sleep, there are slow rolling eye movements with attenuation of the alpha rhythm, vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles.
Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is relatively asleep with features of stage II sleep identified during photic stimulation.  While there is a low voltage, symmetric brief driving response following photic stimulation as the patient drifts off to sleep, there are two bursts of symmetric, low voltage TFA.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG to due to:
Brief bursts of generalized paroxysmal fast activity identified following photic stimulation in a state of relative drowsiness.
A single left anterior temporal sharp wave.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This is the third EEG for this patient.  The GPFA is similar to abnormalities identified on the October 5, 2000 EEG.  The 1994 EEG was normal, and the 2002 EEG identified some left 5 Hz activity from the occipital scalp region.  The major relevant difference between the two EEGs is the presence of a discrete, left frontal sharp wave.  This has been reported in the literature as part of the maturational process of a primary generalized epilepsy, but it could also be seen in the setting of a partial or focal epilepsy as well.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG to due to Brief bursts of generalized paroxysmal fast activity identified following photic stimulation in a state of relative drowsiness. A single left anterior temporal sharp wave.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 56-year-old woman with primary generalized epilepsy, history of myoclonic and absence seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Lamictal.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1  channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness there is 8Hz posterior dominant rhythm.
In hyperventilation and in drowsiness,  however, there is more rhythmic 5Hz background theta with almost a rhythmic 5Hz posterior dominant rhythm.
There are intermittent bursts of frontally predominant generalized spike and wave and polyspike and wave activity. These occur in hyperventilation and are of 3-5 seconds duration. They are seen post hyperventilation in bursts lasting approximately 3 seconds in duration. The last burst is seen at 120 seconds post hyperventilation as the patient transitions into sleep.  Additional bursts are seen in the transition to stage I sleep.  They do not clearly produce an arousal response, although the first burst is seen in the first transition to sleep.  Other features of stage II  sleep include spindles and posts.
Photic stimulation elicits a driving response.   On 1 occasion the spike and wave activity also seems to be associated with the photic stimulation.
Heart rate: 70 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Bursts of 3-5Hz frontally predominant spike and wave activity and polyspike and wave activity.
2.	Spike and wave activity seen in hyperventilation and 1 time photic stimulation.
3.	Rhythmic theta activity, greater than one might expect in wakefulness and early drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The primary epileptiform abnormality in this record is generalized spike and wave activity as was previously identified.  There are a number of other normal variants or mild abnormalities, including the prominent 5 Hz activity identified. There is also some psychomotor variant, which in this case is likely a normal variant.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Bursts of 3-5Hz frontally predominant spike and wave activity and polyspike and wave activity. 2.Spike and wave activity seen in hyperventilation and 1 time photic stimulation. 3.Rhythmic theta activity, greater than one might expect in wakefulness and early drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 62-year-old woman with adult-onset epilepsy. Prior  EEGs with frontally predominant 3-5 hertz spike and wave activity. Now 2 seizures in the last 9 months, 1 associated with sleep deprivation and alcohol ingestion and the 2nd with dehydration. The patient is not experiencing absence or myoclonic seizures at this time.
MEDICINES:  Lamictal, others.
INTRODUCTION:  A 20-minute digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background includes a 9 Hz alpha rhythm, which is symmetric and reactive.  There is generous background beta.  Notable in this record is an occipitally predominant 5 hertz rhythmic discharge.  It is occipitally predominant and has at times almost a spike and wave complex.  It is typically more prominent in the right occipital region than the left, although on occasion, does appear to be a bit more prominent on the left.
The discharge is prominent at the midline with a slight predominance to the left.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation clearly accentuate this discharge.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in beta.
Heart rate:  60 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Posteriorly predominant, right greater than left, 5 hertz discharge.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The activity described above is probably an epileptiform variant and may be related to this patient's previous generalized spike and wave discharge.  The activity is more prominent at the midline and just to the right of the midline, although it is sometimes seen on the left. No clinical events were recorded.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Posteriorly predominant, right greater than left, 5 hertz discharge.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 39-year-old, right-handed male with closed head injury, several seizures per year, restrictive pulmonary disease, and sleep disturbance.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote, Elavil, Seroquel, asthma medications.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with symmetric, reactive 10 Hz, 30 to 50 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. In both hyperventilation and in drowsiness, there is an increase in shifting, right or left temporal theta, as well as some sharply contoured theta frequency activity which reaches higher amplitudes up to 70 V from the right mid-to-anterior temporal region.   Stage II sleep is characterized by symmetric vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles.
Photic stimulation elicits symmetric driving, as well as LAMBDA waves.
HR:  78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to:
1.	The appearance of shifting, right greater than left temporal theta in drowsiness and hyperventilation with higher amplitude, more sharply contoured theta activity from the right identified on one occasion from the temporal regions and on one occasion from the parietal regions.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The features described above are non-specific.  They support a process involving the temporal regions and the right hemisphere more strongly than the left.  While there are no definite epileptiform discharges, the sharply contoured higher amplitude theta from the right hemisphere is suggestive of such a process.  Correlation with imaging and previous EEGs may be of use.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to 1.The appearance of shifting, right greater than left temporal theta in drowsiness and hyperventilation with higher amplitude, more sharply contoured theta activity from the right identified on one occasion from the temporal regions and on one occasion from the parietal regions.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 17-year-old, right-handed female in a motor vehicle accident in December 1996, meningitis 2000, fall down the stairs with recurrent falling and loss of consciousness.  Diagnosis of non-epileptic seizures made in the emergency room at Frankford. Multiple episodes of confusion and daily seizures versus pseudo-seizures.
MEDICATIONS: None at present.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  The patient experiences a single episode of left leg shaking.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with symmetric, reactive 10 Hz, 25 V posterior dominant rhythm and occasional posterior slow waves of youth.  In the transition to drowsiness, on rare occasions, there is subtle, rhythmic theta activity identified from the left anterior temporal and frontal region.  On one occasion, this activity is also identified in hyperventilation.  Features of stage I sleep include high amplitude vertex waves.
Hyperventilation elicits a rare burst of slowing described above as well as bursts of rhythmic, high amplitude 3 Hz activity which is well formed, but without definite spike or slow wave activity underlying it.
Photic stimulation elicits symmetric driving.
The patient had a single episode of right leg shaking.  This occurred after hyperventilation.  The EEG at this time identified a normal awake pattern.  The patient was able to answer questions throughout.  The activity lasted about 90 seconds and there was a bit of head bobbing associated with it.
HR:  __ BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Subtle focal slowing from the left anterior temporal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The behavior recorded during this EEG did not have an EEG correlate.  The subtle focal slowing described above is of unclear clinical significance.  Correlation with history and imaging is recommended.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Subtle focal slowing from the left anterior temporal region.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 17-year-old, right-handed female with hypothyroidism and a question of seizures versus non-epileptic seizures. Her history is multiple episodes with bilateral shaking without loss of consciousness.  These have occurred during previous EEGs without an EEG correlate.
MEDICATIONS: Synthroid
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  This was a fasting record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with symmetric, reactive 10 Hz alpha rhythm reaching amplitudes up to 70  V with posterior slow waves of youth. Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record and elicits initially subtle, left temporal sharply contoured theta, which is somewhat irregular.  There appears to be a sharp wave varied in this frontotemporal theta.  The sharp wave can be identified on three different occasions.  Review of this activity with reformatting suggests a maximum at F7 but on other occasions in the left frontal region.  As hyperventilation continues, there are bursts of synchronous, high amplitude rhythmic frontally predominant delta.  Features of stage II sleep include high amplitude vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles.  Photic stimulation elicits symmetric driving.
HR:  96 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Left anterior temporal focal slowing with a suspicious underlying sharp wave.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This second record again identifies left anterior temporal focal slowing.  The suspicious sharp wave merits additional evaluation to determine whether or not this patient is having behaviors which are seizures in addition to the behaviors which appear to have been confirmed not to be epileptiform.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.Left anterior temporal focal slowing with a suspicious underlying sharp wave.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 20-year-old woman with epilepsy since age 15, seizure-free for “awhile,” but with a seizure one year ago with loss of consciousness and generalized tonic-clonic activity, but no postictal confusion.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 12 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm with a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements with an increase in faster frequency activity and then attenuation of the alpha with background theta.  Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained.  Photic stimulation is remarkable for LAMBDA activity, but also some driving at faster flash frequencies.  Hyperventilation produces a generous burst of high amplitude, frontally predominant 3 to 5 Hz activity.  The patient reports feeling tingling in the mouth and hands during HV.  The data is re-reviewed with appropriate sensitivities and even with fewer channels per page to make sure that there is no underlying spike and wave activity, and none can be determined
HR:  96 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG for an adult of this age in wakefulness and brief drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 53-year-old, left-handed woman with a history of brain tumor resection one year ago. She presents with complaints of severe headache and seizures with loss of consciousness (tonic-clonic seizures).  Diabetes mellitus, arthritis, and blood clot in the left leg.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: There is a 7 Hz, 30 to 60 V dominant rhythm.  Intermittent bilateral as well as unilateral right focal slowing is characterized by frontal theta and delta.  There is a right frontal breech demonstrated by increased beta and increased amplitude of theta.  As the patient becomes drowsy, there are more prominent bursts of frontal slowing and a breech on the right.  Although the EEG is abnormal, it is nearly symmetric and well organized at times. Hyperventilation produces right frontal delta.  Photic stimulation elicits symmetric driving.  There is no EEG change at the time of twitching.
HR:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Intermittent bilateral as well as unilateral focal slowing characterized by frontal theta or delta.
Right frontal breech with increased beta and increased amplitude of the delta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing suggests an underlying structural problem most likely affecting both frontal hemispheres. No sharp waves could be identified. A follow-up EEG during deeper stages of sleep may be useful in identifying focal epileptiform activity given the breech rhythm.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Intermittent bilateral as well as unilateral focal slowing characterized by frontal theta or delta. Right frontal breech with increased beta and increased amplitude of the delta.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 38-year-old female with epilepsy. No other details are known and no seizure history is known.
MEDICATIONS: Unknown.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were attempted.  The patient spoke no English and had no caregiver to help translate. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The initial portions of the record are well-organized with a 9.25 Hz, 40 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  In the initial portions of the record, the patient is a bit drowsy and hyperventilation is attempted.  There are bursts seen in this portion of the record in the temporal regions.  There are irregular bursts, which appear in the left or right temporal regions, sometimes a bit more on one side than the other or starting on the left and going to right or vice versa.  With the use of the T1-T2 electrodes, the activity appears to be maximum at T1 and there is an underlying sharp wave at T1-T3.  This becomes more prominent in the later HV recording. In these bursts, there are also T2 sharp waves and a sharply contoured background.  Following hyperventilation, as the patient becomes drowsy, there are additional sharp waves again seen at T1.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in the irregular temporal theta and the occasional sharp waves.  Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained.
Photic stimulation did not significantly activate the record.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Irregular temporal slowing with an unusual field of spread often involving both temporal regions but asynchronous.
Left greater than right temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a partial mechanism for epilepsy.  If further characterization of this patient’s epilepsy is needed, an additional recording capturing sleep or one of her seizures would be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Irregular temporal slowing with an unusual field of spread often involving both temporal regions but asynchronous. Left greater than right temporal sharp waves.

IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record.  The only focal features were artifactual in nature.  In comparison to previous EEGs, there are no generalized nor focal epileptiform abnormalities identified at this time.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 20-year-old woman with complex epilepsy, complicated labor and delivery, MVA as a child, seizures characterized by frontal headache followed by a feeling as if she is floating, which may be associated with visual phenomenon including circular visual phenomenon and then tonic-clonic activity with incontinence and tongue biting. INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a symmetric, reactive 10 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  In apparent wakefulness, hyperventilation, and early drowsiness, there is subtle, left temporal focal slowing.  There is a single left temporal sharp wave identified early in hyperventilation.  Vertex waves are seen in brief stage I sleep, but stage I sleep is not sustained.  Photic stimulation elicits symmetric, bilateral driving.
HR:  90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Subtle left temporal focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In that only a single sharp wave was identified, additional EEG recording may be useful to clearly define this patient’s epileptiform activity.  Alternatively, comparison with her childhood EEGs may be of use. This tracing supports a structural or functional abnormality on the left.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.Subtle left temporal focal slowing.

report:

report:

Single sharp activity in the left central area.
Subtle sharp activity seen in the right temporal area.

IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to Mildly disorganized background with excessive slow activity for a child of this age. Single sharp activity in the left central area. Subtle sharp activity seen in the right temporal area.

report:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 32-year-old male with a history of frontal lobe confusion.  November 2002 the patient was found sitting in a car after being reported missing for three days.  He has no memory for this.  The other episode occurred in July 2003 when the patient was found to have a dislocated shoulder and started on Dilantin.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake through stage I sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is symmetric and fairly well organized.  There is an 8.5 Hz, 75 to 100 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.   During hyperventilation, occasional bursts of slow theta and delta activity are seen in the left temporal or right temporal area. This burst pattern is also seen in drowsiness.  Drowsiness is characterized by vertex waves. Deeper stages of sleep were not achieved.
Photic stimulation elicits driving.
HR:  56 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Irregular bursts of slow theta and delta activity in the left or right temporal area.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The above finding is a non-specific pattern and may be linked to the underlying pathologic process secondary to the frontal lobe contusion.  However, no epileptiform features were identified in this record.  If epilepsy is a clinical concern, a repeat EEG capturing deeper stages of sleep or sleep deprivation prior to the EEG may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.Irregular bursts of slow theta and delta activity in the left or right temporal area.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 37-year-old male with HIV infection, schizophrenia, hepatitis C, and a question of seizures versus non-epileptic seizures, as well as behavioral issues.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin and HIV medications.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is described as poorly cooperative.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is somewhat slow with a 7 to 8 Hz posterior dominant rhythm and excess background theta, as well as generous, low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  In this background with theta, there is left temporal wicket activity with some wicket identified on the right. In the transition to drowsiness, there are occasional bursts of frontally predominant delta.  Features noted as the patient becomes drowsy include an increase in background beta.  Occasional K complexes are seen in stage II sleep, again followed by arousals.
Hyperventilation is performed with good effort producing a small degree of slowing in the background.  Photic stimulation does not significantly activate this record.
HR:  78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Generalized background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This patient’s medications, hepatic problems, or retroviral infection may all produce the background slowing described above as may a postictal state.  While the wicket is a sharply contoured normal variant, no definite epileptiform features were seen, and a more prolonged recording in stage II sleep may be helpful to identify epileptiform activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.Generalized background slowing.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 39-year-old male with epilepsy and HIV infection with multiple frequent seizures and strong suspicions for non-epileptic seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Ativan, Phenobarbital, and Tylenol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation was performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record. The patient has a long behavioral event and requires Ativan to calm down.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 9 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm.  The patient starts hyperventilation early on in the record without the development of epileptiform activity.  At 11:48:34, he begins to have shaking movements, shaking the head from side to side and arms going up and down.  There are then some rotatory components or circular movements of the head.  The activity waxes and wanes.  The physician comes in to test the patient at 11:55:30.  The patient’s behavior waxes and wanes.  He is examined by a physician and nurse, and is clearly interactive during the spell.  Ativan is given at 16:14 and by 16:17, he is a bit more responsive and interactive.  When asked where he is, he responds that he is at [hospital] Hospital.  The EEG demonstrates a relatively normal pattern by the end with some generous beta.
HR:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The prolonged behavioral event, lasting almost 20 minutes, was not associated with epileptiform activity in the EEG.  Consideration for other diagnostic categories is appropriate.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:

CLINICAL CORRELATION: The focal findings in this tracing are suggestive of an underlying pathological process in this patient and supports a partial mechanism for epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Focal slowing at T6 and O2 accentuated in hyperventilation with subtle 3 Hz slow wave discharges at T6, as well as slowing in the bilateral posterior temporal region.

report:

Modest disorganization.
Occasional FIRDA.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 36-year-old male who fell and hit his head, losing consciousness.  History of cocaine use and prior traumatic brain injury.  CAT scan showed a left parietal subacute effusion.
MEDICATIONS: Antibiotics and others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.  This is an awake through stage II sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is mildly disorganized for age.  There is a 9 Hz, 20 V posterior dominant alpha rhythm, which attenuates with eyes opened.   There is a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  As the recording continues, bilateral focal arrhythmic delta activity, more predominant on the left than the right, is seen.  The patient easily fell asleep, which is evidenced by vertex waves and spindles, as well as a lot of snoring.  The focal slowing was more dramatic during sleep and the asymmetry did not change during sleep.
HR:  108 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Mildly disorganized background.
Focal arrhythmic delta activity, more predominant on the left than the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The focal findings in this EEG are indicative of an underlying pathological process suggestive of a structural lesion. The patient’s loud snoring may be suggestive of obstructive sleep apnea and follow-up with a pulmonologist to rule out a sleep disorder is suggested.  No epileptiform features were identified in this record. If epilepsy is a clinical concern, a repeat EEG may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Mildly disorganized background. Focal arrhythmic delta activity, more predominant on the left than the right.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 19-year-old woman with a history of hypertension, end-stage renal disease on hemodialysis admitted for subdural hemorrhage, which was surgically.  Acute seizures, not described

MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, antihypertensives, and others.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the Neuro ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.  This is an awake record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is continuous and symmetric with generalized slowing.  There is a 7 to 8 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm, which is well attenuated with eyes opened.  There is a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Soon after the EEG commences, the patient began to shake her left arm and then both arms and hands on her abdomen.  The shaking was in a different direction at different rhythms.  The patient could open and close her eyes and follow commands during this episode.  Alternatively, when her left-hand shaking stopped, she began to open and close her legs with shaking, left side worse then the right.  With the prolonged episode, muscle movement artifact can be seen, but no significant EEG changes or correlates were found.  On the video camera, several doctors were called to see the patient.  The patient can open and close her eyes, follow commands, and lift her arms and legs up.  Interestingly, the patientÕs episodes spontaneously subsided if no one paid attention to her and she responded to a placebo of saline injection.  Throughout the EEG, there were no epileptiform discharges, but occasionally sharply contoured delta activity in the left central area is seen.

HR:  116 BPM.

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Diffusely slow background.
2. Occasional sharply contoured delta in the left central area.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: The diffusely slow background, as well as occasional sharply contoured delta activity in the left central area may be suggestive of an underlying pathological process in this patient, which is commonly seen in patients with hypertension and end-stage renal disease on hemodialysis.  This finding can also be seen in patients with subdural hematoma.  During the tracing, the patient had prolonged episodes of arm or leg shaking without EEG change, as well as being responsive to commands.  This is suggestive of non-epileptic seizures.  These findings were communicated with the primary neurosurgery team.  If epilepsy is a clinical concern or clinically indicated, when the patient is more stable and cooperative, a repeat EEG in the lab with full activation including hyperventilation and photic stimulation, as well as capturing deeper stages of sleep may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Diffusely slow background. 2. Occasional sharply contoured delta in the left central area.

report:

report:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 31-year-old male with childhood epilepsy, seizure free until recent years.  Patient states that he is currently seizure-free for the past year.
MEDICATIONS:  Lamictal, Keppra, retrovirals.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm.  A subtle asymmetry is noted between the 2 hemispheres with a bit of 7 Hz theta noted in the right hemisphere relative to the left and very subtle disruption of the alpha rhythm on the right.  As the patient becomes drowsy, the record becomes increasingly synchronous and symmetric.  Other features of drowsiness include rhythmic background theta and attenuation of the alpha rhythm.  Brief spindles were noted with POSTS in stage 2 sleep.  Photic stimulation was performed as the patient is drifting in to stage 2 sleep, and did not significantly activate the record.  Hyperventilation produced a vigorous hyperventilation response with an increase in rhythmic theta as well as an increase in beta.  There is some subtle, asymmetric bursts noted in hyperventilation with higher amplitude rhythmic theta noted on the left.  There is one, suspicious underlying sharp waves noted at the close of hyperventilation in the right centrotemporal region.
Heart rate 56 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is a subtly abnormal EEG due to:
A very subtle asymmetry, identified using a frequency analysis with an increase in 7 Hz activity noted intermittently in the right hemisphere with disruption of the alpha rhythm.
An asynchronous hyperventilation response with higher amplitude rhythmic theta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Only a single sharp wave was seen there for this must not be considered definitively epileptogenic.  This is the 7th EEG for this individual.  Previous EEGs have identified right mid temporal sharp waves, which were not identified at this time.  This patient's 2004-2008 EEGs were not available for comparison.  No prominent epileptiform or focal features were noted, and no new findings were noted in this record.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is a subtly abnormal EEG due to A very subtle asymmetry, identified using a frequency analysis with an increase in 7 Hz activity noted intermittently in the right hemisphere with disruption of the alpha rhythm. An asynchronous hyperventilation response with higher amplitude rhythmic theta.

report:
HISTORY:

34 y.o. male with a history of childhood seizures, now with episodes on
awakening from sleep with trembling, nausea, shortness of breath and lightheadedness, referred for
routine EEG for evaluate for possible seizure activity.




MEDICATIONS:

Current Outpatient Prescriptions:


efavirenz-emtrictabine-tenofovir (ATRIPLA) 600-200-300 mg per tablet, TAKE 1 TABLET BY
MOUTH NIGHTLY.

efavirenz-emtrictabine-tenofovir (ATRIPLA) 600-200-300 mg per tablet, TAKE 1 TABLET BY
MOUTH NIGHTLY.


lamoTRIgine (LAMICTAL) 200 mg tablet, Take 1 tablet by mouth 2 times daily.



No current facility-administered medications for this visit.




SEDATION: None




TECHNIQUE:


A  Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20
system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record
and included a single channel of EKG, hyperventilation, and photic stimulation.



EEG BACKGROUND:


Wakefulness is characterized by symmetric and reactive 9-10 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm (PDR)
which attenuates symmetrically with eye opening. Low amplitude symmetric 18-30 Hz activity was
seen anteriorly, with superimposed muscle and frontal eye blink artifact



During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior
dominant rhythm, and diffuse background slowing are seen.




Sleep is characterized by normal sleep transients, with synchronous and symmetric vertex waves,
sleep spindles and K-complexes. Slow wave sleep was not captured.




EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:

No epileptiform activity is present.



OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):

None



ACTIVATION PROCEDURES:



Hyperventilation: Hyperventilation is performed for 180 seconds with good cooperation and produces
mild diffuse symmetric background slowing.



Photic Stimulation: Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces
symmetric photic driving, which is a normal finding.



EVENTS:

There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.



HEART RATE:

A heart rate of 64 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.






IMPRESSION:

This is a normal awake and asleep routine EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic events
reported or detected.




A normal routine EEG does not support or refute the diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 
This is a normal awake and asleep routine EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic events
reported or detected

report:

report:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 55-year-old male with epilepsy.  Patient had one event during the EEG characterized by tenseness with eyes opened, not focused, mild tremulousness of body and legs, and unable to respond to questions during the event.  The patient was somewhat confused for 1.5 minutes afterwards.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol, Norvasc, Lasix, and Lipitor.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 9 Hz, 30 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Photic stimulation is performed early on in the record.  A brief driving response is seen, but as the patient relaxes a little bit further, subtle left temporal slowing is seen.  Hyperventilation is performed subsequently and the subtle focal features can be identified.  A seizure occurred following hyperventilation and post-hyperventilation.  Post-hyperventilation, the focal slowing gradually increases 20 seconds after the onset of hyperventilation.  The seizure onset is at 14:08:37 with no clinical signs, but high amplitude spike and slow wave activity with rhythmic delta and then high amplitude delta and sharply contoured delta with a clear phase reversal at T1.  The patient starts to arouse at 14:08:57, opening his eyes and then stiffening.  He is slightly tremulous and demonstrates chewing movements.  The activity makes the transition to repetitive alpha frequency activity and then 5 Hz frequency activity by 14:09:17.  The activity begins to slow and ends at 14:09:38 for an approximate one-minute seizure duration.  The background EEG demonstrates postictal slowing in the minutes that follow, which gradually resolves.  The patient is unable to speak during the seizure and in the postictal period he nods his head from side to side.  He has a relatively lengthy postictal period including almost all the way to the end of the record.  Over time, he becomes increasingly able to speak, although initially he answers all questions with “uhm-uhm” noise.  Over time, he can answer questions, but has difficulty performing simple tasks.
HR:  94 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Left temporal seizure, relatively well characterized by scalp EEG.
Left temporal focal slowing with rare sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Diagnostic of a partial mechanism for epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Left temporal seizure, relatively well characterized by scalp EEG. Left temporal focal slowing with rare sharp waves.

report:

INTRODUCTION: Digital  video  EEG is performed  in the  lab using  standard  10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation  and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake through stage II sleep record.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 39-year-old former preemie with a history of childhood epilepsy, seizure-free for many years with an episode of staring and shaking without impairment of awareness.  The patient describes this as not typical for her seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Dilaudid, Morphine, Zofran, and Ativan.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, there is an 8.5 Hz, 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm.  Although there is some head rocking artifact, there is intermittent rhythmic 5 Hz theta activity identified from the posterior regions, slightly more prominent in the right compared to the left.  This occipitally predominant rhythmic theta is accentuated by hyperventilation. Features of drowsiness include attenuation of the alpha rhythm.  Unfortunately, the head rocking persists in the right posterior quadrant.
Photic stimulation is remarkable for a vigorous driving response at nearly all flash frequencies, with a high amplitude, well-formed spiky driving response, but without definite spike and slow wave activity.
HR:  92 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for a subject of this age due to:
Occipitally predominant rhythmic theta.
?Right occipitally predominant focal slowing in the setting of a single channel artifact.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There are no definite epileptiform features. If further characterization of this patient’s epilepsy is important, an additional study with more sustained sleep, focusing on the right occipital temporal region would be appropriate.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for a subject of this age due to Occipitally predominant rhythmic theta. ?Right occipitally predominant focal slowing in the setting of a single channel artifact.

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Intra hemispheric asymmetry with slowing of the right hemisphere which includes

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 50-year-old woman with adult onset epilepsy.  Family says she has not been taking her medicines, admitted with recurrent seizures characterized by head turning to the left and posturing.
MEDICATIONS:  Ativan and Trileptal.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the emergency room using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Patient was postictal, wearing a face mask and poorly cooperative.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Background EEG is abnormal and at times, partially obscured by muscle and movement artifact.  The overall background is slow.  Superimposed upon this, there is an asymmetry with more arrhythmic delta activity and disruption of faster frequency activity on the right relative to the left.  There are bursts of irregular theta delta with underlying sharp waves noted from the right hemisphere.  The irregular epileptiform activity demonstrates variable maximum, but is typically maximum in the right posterior quadrant or T4, P4T6.  In addition, there is handful of bursts of more right frontotemporal rhythmic slowing and a handful of lower voltage discrete F8 sharp waves.
Stimulation of the patient produces an increase in muscle and movement.
Heart rate 66 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Background slowing and disorganization.
Superimposed focal slowing from the right hemisphere, particularly right temporal region.
Irregular epileptiform activity in the right hemisphere particularly posterior quadrant, but at some points more anteriorly, anterior frontotemporal pathology.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This patient's previous baseline EEG on long-term monitoring are not available at this time for comparison.  This EEG supports a localization related mechanism for epilepsy.  EEG monitoring will continue.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Background slowing and disorganization. Superimposed focal slowing from the right hemisphere, particularly right temporal region. Irregular epileptiform activity in the right hemisphere particularly posterior quadrant, but at some points more anteriorly, anterior frontotemporal pathology.

report:
History:	46 year old man with a history of seizures and headaches.
Medications:	Depakote - but patient is not compliant
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Awake & asleep
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 9.5Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  During drowsiness, the background slows to central theta activity, frontal
beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes intermittent.
During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces mild diffuse
symmetric background slowing.  Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps)
induces symmetric photic driving at multiple flash rates.
Summary of Findings:
Sleep, stage 2
No epileptiform discharges
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 22-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. The lack of epileptiform discharges
on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL 22-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. The lack of epileptiform discharges
on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy

CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 40-year-old woman with epilepsy following a craniotomy for aneurysm.  Hypertension and depression.  Last seizure one month ago.
MEDICATIONS: Wellbutrin, Zoloft, Abilify, morphine, methadone, Dilantin, and HCTZ.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record. The patient’s previous EEGs were not available at this time.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is an 11 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm with a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  There is intermittent rhythmic theta from the left hemisphere.  Although there is a breach rhythm, and there is some muscle artifact, there appears to be an underlying spike and slow wave complex identified from the left mid-temporal region, accentuated by hyperventilation.  Following hyperventilation, the patient becomes drowsy and in drowsiness there are vertex waves and POSTS.  The amplitude is somewhat higher from the left than the right, accentuating the POSTS on the left.  As the patient reaches sleep, in this sharply contoured background, there is both accentuation of beta on the left but there are a handful of sharp waves that also come out of this background.  Snore artifact is also identified in stage II sleep.
Photic stimulation elicits a driving response, which is markedly accentuated on the left.
HR:  54 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Left temporal theta accentuated by drowsiness and hyperventilation.
Left temporal sharp waves in hyperventilation and in stage II sleep.  The morphology is compatible with a breach rhythm.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The prominent breach rhythm accentuates the beta activity in stage II sleep and produces an increase in the amplitude of the background in photic stimulation, but is simply a manifestation of the previous craniotomy.  The focal slowing and sharp waves supports a temporal lobe disturbance and a localization-related mechanism for seizures.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Left temporal theta accentuated by drowsiness and hyperventilation. Left temporal sharp waves in hyperventilation and in stage II sleep.  The morphology is compatible with a breach rhythm.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 43 year old woman with left aneurysm clip craniotomy, seizure
free for 2 years. Depression and hypertension.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra, HCTZ
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
simulation are performed. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: Much of the record includes a drowsy state with
generous beta. A breach rhythm is identified in the left frontocentral region. In addition, occasional left temporal rhythmic focal slowing and sharp waves are noted in both wakefulness, hyperventilation, and drowsiness. These are discrete and can be
differentiated from the patient's EKG artifact. Scant wakefulness includes a symmetric reactive posterior dominate rhythm.
HR: 66 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Left temporal focal slowing.
2. Left temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This is the patient's 4th EEG. The 2006 study
demonstrated both focal slowing and sharp waves, although the follow-up EEGs
demonstrated only focal slowing, focal delta. The individual remains seizure free, but
these findings support a localized mechanism for epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Left temporal focal slowing. 2. Left temporal sharp waves.

TECHNIQUE:

A one hour Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the
International 10-20 system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a
technically satisfactory record and included a single channel of EKG, HV and photic stimulation.




EEG BACKGROUND:

The waking background is low voltage, symmetric, reactive, and consists of a mixture of alpha and a
moderate amount of bifrontal beta activity, organized in a normal anterior-to-posterior gradient.
Wakefulness is characterized by a symmetric and reactive 12 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm (PDR),
which attenuates symmetrically with eye opening. There is prominent diffuse beta.




During drowsiness, there is slowing of the PDR followed by slow rolling eye movements, attenuation
and fragmentation of the posterior dominant rhythm, and diffuse background slowing are seen.
There was generous beta.




Sleep is characterized by normal sleep transients, with synchronous and symmetric vertex waves,
POSTs, sleep spindles and K-complexes. Slow wave sleep was not captured. There is generous beta
noted in drowsiness.




No generalized slowing is present.  No focal slowing is present.


EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:


No epileptiform activity is present.


OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):


None

Wicket is seen.





ACTIVATION PROCEDURES:



Hyperventilation: produces an increase in amplitude in the background.



Photic Stimulation: a driving response is seen although the patient was falling asleep during photic
stimulation.



EVENTS:

There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.



HEART RATE:

A heart rate of 72 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.



IMPRESSION:

This is a normal awake and asleep routine EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic events
reported or detected.



CLINICAL CORRELATION:


A normal routine EEG does not support or refute the diagnosis of epilepsy. There is generous beta
noted in this record. This is also a low voltage pattern. These findings can be seen in normal adults.


This individual has 6 prior EEGs. Four were available for review. Three, 2010, 2008, 2007
demonstrated left temporal sharp waves.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 
This is a normal awake and asleep routine EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic events
reported or detected.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 54 year old male with liver transplant, postoperative course, hepatitis C, thrombocytopenia and hepatic encephalopathy.

MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Lamictal, Coumadin, Simethicone, Warfarin, Midodrine, Florinef, Metoprolol, Neurontin, Cyclosporine, Synthroid, Testosterone, Advair, Prednisone, Valcyte, Protonix, Fluconazole, Bactrim

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. The patient is poorly responsive.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is slow, a theta pattern. With stimulation, there is an increase in faster frequency activity. There is an area of sharply contoured slowing in the right posterior temporal region. Stimulation of the patient clearly produces an alerting response, but when stimulation ends, the patient drifts off to sleep with vertex waves and spindles. These focal features in the right posterior quadrant are not as remarkable in sleep.

HR: 90 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. General background slowing.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This individual previously had generalized spike and wave activity. The background slowing may be part of a metabolic encephalopathy. The focal findings may be correlated with imaging and exam.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. General background slowing.

report:

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside in using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. The patient is drowsy.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates a somewhat slow pattern with excess background theta. There are intermittent bursts of 4 to 6 Hz frontally, predominant spike in wave and poly spike in wave activity as well as occasional bursts of GTFA activity.

1. Mild background slowing.

IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Mild background slowing. 2. Occasional generalized poly spiked activity as well as spike in wave activity.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 56 year old left handed woman with history of seizures, now admitted after multiple recurrent seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Propofol.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video long term monitoring, 6 hours EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrodes.  Wakefulness and sleep were recorded.  No activating procedures were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  After 10:00 at night until 6:00 in the morning from November 6 to November 7, 2011 there was marked muscle and multielectrode artifact to almost impossible reading the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record at the beginning opens to a diffusely slow low amplitude recording with no clear posterior dominant rhythm.  By 2 hours into the recording faster frequencies can be seen and improvement of the EEG to baseline was seen.  At best the posterior dominant rhythm reaches 8 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  There is a small amount of frontal central beta seen.  Some sleep architecture is seen.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Occasional bursts of polyspike and generalized spike and waves seen at 4.5 to 5 Hz with anterior predominance  symmetrically over both hemispheres.  None of the bursts last more than 1 second.
Generalized slow waves at 5-7 Hz and 20-60 mV amplitude.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized spikes and waves.
Polyspikes and excessive theta in wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The EEG findings are consistent with those of idiopathic generalized epilepsy.  In addition, there is evidence of mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  In this patient it is likely due, at least in part, to medication effect.  No seizures were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Generalized spikes and waves. Polyspikes and excessive theta in wakefulness.

HISTORY:

60 y.o. male with a history of JME and

possible focal seizures, presenting with fever and altered mental


status; referred for routine EEG for assessment of mental status

change.



MEDICATIONS: MYCOPHENOLATE MOFETIL, ALBUTEROL, VANCOMYCIN,

KEPPRA, VIMPAT, HEPARIN, LASIX, ASA, SIROLIMUS, THERAGRAN,

PLAVIX, PRAVACHOL, PROTONIX



SEDATION: None



TECHNIQUE:

A 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the

International 10-20 system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a


NicOne system. This was at times a technically difficult study,




with muscle artifact obscuring the temporal chains. It included a

single channel of EKG and photic stimulation.



EEG BACKGROUND:


The waking background is continuous and symmetric but consists of

fairly organized sharply contoured delta and theta frequencies,

with admixed faster frequencies. Delta frequencies are seen more

posteriorly.  Fragments of an irregular posterior dominant rhythm


approach 6-7 Hz.



Drowsiness is characterized by further background slowing.

Sleep transients are not captured.


Moderate generalized slowing is present.


There is frequent bilateral posterior quadrant polymorphic

slowing.



EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:

Occasional diffuse frontally predominant polyspikes with shifting

predomiance.



OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):


None


ACTIVATION PROCEDURES:



Hyperventilation: Hyperventilation is not performed.



Photic Stimulation: Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21

flashes per second (fps) does not produce any EEG changes.


EVENTS:


There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during

this study.



HEART RATE:


A heart rate of 90 bpm, with frequent PVCs, is captured on a

single EKG lead.



IMPRESSION:


This is an abnormal awake and drowsy  routine EEG due to:

1. Moderate generalized slowing

2. Suboptimal organization

3. Frequent bilateral posterior quadrant polymorphic slowing


4. Occasional diffuse frontally predominant polyspikes with

shifting predominance


5. A heart rate of 90 with frequent PVCs is captured on a single

EKG lead


CLINICAL CORRELATION:


These findings indicate the presence of diffuse epileptogenic

potential superimposed on bilateral posterior quadrant


dysfunction and moderate diffuse cerebral dysfunction.

Frequent PVCs are seen on a single EKG lead.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 

This is an abnormal awake and drowsy  routine EEG due to 
1. Moderate generalized slowing

2. Suboptimal organization

3. Frequent bilateral posterior quadrant polymorphic slowing


4. Occasional diffuse frontally predominant polyspikes with

shifting predominance


5. A heart rate of 90 with frequent PVCs is captured on a single

EKG lead

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 78-year-old male with episodes of syncope and presyncope with a vasovagal episode in the bathroom associated with a small right cortical hemorrhage, followed a day later by a left posteriotemporal intraparenchymal hemorrhage.
MEDICATIONS: Flomax, Trileptal.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm.  The overall background includes excess background theta.  There is intermittent arrhythmic delta activity seen from the temporal regions more prominent from the left posterior temporal region, but seen occasionally on the right.  There are rare left temporal sharp waves seen in wakefulness.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in background slowing.  Photic stimulation does not activate the record.
HR:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Arrhythmic delta from the left mid-temporal region.
Rare sharp waves.
Shifting arrhythmic temporal delta from either side.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:   Supports localization mechanism for epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Arrhythmic delta from the left mid-temporal region. Rare sharp waves. Shifting arrhythmic temporal delta from either side.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 44-year-old woman with epilepsy since childhood whose last seizure was three days ago.  Her seizures are described as left-sided shaking with subsequent loss of consciousness and generalized convulsions, which is followed by postictal confusion.  Frequency of seizures is one to two times per year.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the overall background EEG is fairly well organized with a 9.5 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm.  There is mild excess theta seen in the background.  Occasional sharply contoured left mid-temporal delta is seen, which is accentuated in hyperventilation and post-hyperventilation.  The focal slowing is accompanied by occasional sharp waves at T1.  There is also one single right centrotemporal sharp wave identified. Photic stimulation elicits brief, symmetric driving.  Throughout the tracing, there is artifact originating from impedance issues at the T3 electrodes.
HR:  87 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Mild excess theta.
Occasional left mid-temporal focal slowing with sharp waves.
One single right centrotemporal sharp wave.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a partial or localization-related mechanism for epilepsy in this patient.  The technical problems seen in this record due to impedance issues at the P3 electrode, may have partially obscured important references, therefore, obscuring underlying sharp waves, a repeat study would be valuable. Correlation with neuroimaging would also be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Mild excess theta. Occasional left mid-temporal focal slowing with sharp waves. One single right centrotemporal sharp wave.

report:

Frontally predominant intermittent rhythmic delta.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 50-year-old woman with renal failure admitted in June.  Question subarachnoid hemorrhage with a confusional spell versus convulsion.
MEDICATIONS: Lipitor, Clonidine, Oxycodone.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with an 11 Hz, 40 to 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm.  Hyperventilation is performed with good effort, producing an increase in the amplitude of the background but no focal features.  Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements followed by the appearance of vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and POSTS in stage II sleep.
The patient is falling asleep in photic stimulation, and most of photic stimulation demonstrates stage II sleep, although there are some LAMBDA waves.
HR:  78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG contrast to a previous study on 6/8/06, which identified FIRDA and excess theta.  There were no focal or epileptiform features identified in this record.  Of note, this patient had already discontinued her antiepileptic medication one month ago.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 23-year-old woman with two first-ever seizures occurring during sleep with postictal confusion, but no incontinence.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake through stage II sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized for an adult of this age with a symmetric, reactive 10.5 Hz alpha rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Features of drowsiness include vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and POSTS.  Hyperventilation is performed with good effort, producing an increase in the amplitude of the background.
Towards the close of the record, as the patient is in stage II sleep and photic stimulation begins, there is some artifact but there are also some pairs of suspicious underlying left centrotemporal sharp waves of low amplitude and discrete, but appear to be interrupting the background.  The patient otherwise remains in stage II sleep during photic. Low voltage left temporal sharp waves are seen only in this section of the record, and almost seem to have an electropositivity between T3 and F7, but do appear to have otherwise a clear field in the left centrotemporal and posteriotemporal regions.
HR:  70 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Unusual but abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Suspicious left temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Additional EEG recording with special electrodes or special techniques may be helpful to more clearly evaluate the underlying dipole that produces this activity and to be more certain that it is not artifactual in nature.  Correlation with imaging may also be valuable for this adult with new onset seizures.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Unusual but abnormal EEG due to 1.Suspicious left temporal sharp waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 62-year-old male with epilepsy since age 17 with recurrent seizures one year ago, but none recalled by the patient for the last year.  He has been living in a nursing home.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin and Neurontin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is relatively low voltage.  Hyperventilation is performed with good effort, producing an increase in the amplitude of the background.  At that time, a low voltage 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm is identified bilaterally.  Despite movement artifact, there is a glimpse of a left mid-to-anterior temporal region in HV.  This is followed by a drowsy pattern at which point there is some subtle focal slowing discernable in the left anteriotemporal region.  As the patient drifts off to sleep, he begins to snore, again producing a fair amount of artifact.  Other features of sleep include some vertex activity.   In sleep, well-defined left anteriotemporal spike and slow wave complexes are identified.  The patient remains asleep during photic stimulation, with features of stage II sleep and spindles, but no clear driving.  In this sleep state, during HV, the left anteriotemporal spike and slow wave complexes are better defined and then the patient briefly awakens towards the end of HV.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Left anteriotemporal spike and slow wave activity.
Left anteriotemporal focal slowing.
Low voltage, somewhat slow background.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Despite the technical challenges described above, this EEG is similar to a previous record with focal temporal epileptiform activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Left anteriotemporal spike and slow wave activity. Left anteriotemporal focal slowing. Low voltage, somewhat slow background.

report:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 31-year-old male with epilepsy since age 4 following MVA.  Last seizure three to four years ago with postictal confusion.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm.  In wakefulness and in hyperventilation, there is subtle underlying slowing with initially some arrhythmic delta activity seen from the right hemisphere, sometimes with disruption of the alpha rhythm. As HV continues, some shifting slowing is seen.  Features of drowsiness include a decrease in eye movements.  Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained. Photic stimulation elicits scant bilateral driving.
HR:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to:
Subtle underlying arrhythmic slowing, a bit more prominent from the right particularly in hyperventilation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No definite epileptiform features were identified in this record.  If characterization of underlying spike and slow wave activity is important, a repeat tracing capturing sleep may be helpful.  This EEG supports a process, perhaps involving the right hemisphere more than the left, but there is some shifting features to suggest that both hemispheres may have been impacted.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to Subtle underlying arrhythmic slowing, a bit more prominent from the right particularly in hyperventilation.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 20-year-old woman with recent onset epilepsy and seizures, which often can be eliminated by the patient with reassurance.  The patient had six seizures after she ran out of her Effexor.  Patient had a spell immediately upon cessation of the EEG characterized by staring and blinking.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Effexor, Ativan.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing opens, the patient is awake.  There is a 9 to 10 Hz posterior dominant rhythm and a fair amount of eye artifact.   Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record and does elicit some left anteriotemporal sharp and slow wave complexes in association with hyperventilation. Following hyperventilation, the patient becomes somewhat drowsy and there is a small amount of slowing in the left mid-temporal region in this somewhat drowsy pattern.  There is also a high amplitude left anteriotemporal spike and slow wave complex.  As the patient becomes drowsy, there is a left anteriotemporal spike component, but this has a bifrontal field.  This activity can be reviewed with other montages where again it seems to be primarily left temporal with some spread into the eye movement channel.  It is prominent with almost a focal spike and wave component as the patient becomes drowsy and reaches stage II sleep.  Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is in stage II sleep and does not significantly activate the record.  The record ends at 13:45 and the seizure is not captured on the video or the EEG.
HR:  96 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for this individual due to:
Focal, high amplitude spike and slow wave activity identified from the left anteriotemporal region with almost a focal spike and wave component.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: These features differ significantly from previous EEGs and suggests that additional recording and additional evaluation is warranted.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for this individual due to Focal, high amplitude spike and slow wave activity identified from the left anteriotemporal region with almost a focal spike and wave component.
