report:
﻿CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 19-year-old male with epilepsy following head trauma at age six when he was run over by a car.  Patient seizure-free since age 13, now with twitching of the limbs lasting for 20 seconds.  Symptoms start and stop and then move up and down the limbs.  They are not associated with loss of consciousness.

MEDICATIONS:

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: There is limited maximal wakefulness with a well-defined alpha rhythm.  The alpha frequency is 12 Hz, 30 to 50 uV and is slightly higher amplitude on the left compared to the right.  Much of the record includes drowsiness or sleep with slow rolling eye movements and attenuation of the alpha rhythm.  In the transition to sleep, there is a drowsy pattern with rhythmic theta, which is identified bilaterally and is symmetric.  There is a slight amplitude asymmetry on some occasions as slowing develops in the record, with again slightly higher amplitude slowing from the left compared to the right.  Vertex waves in stage I sleep are symmetric.  POSTS are identified bilaterally.

Hyperventilation is performed with good effort, producing an increase in background beta.  Notably, at baseline, the patient’s heart rate is 72 BPM and irregular.  In hyperventilation, the heart rate becomes more irregular, increasing to 96 BPM and is associated with the feeling of light-headedness and a twitchy feeling.  The twitchy feeling is identified at 13:51.  No epileptiform features are identified at that time, although there is an increase in background beta.

Photic stimulation elicits a driving response bilaterally.  The driving response is quite vigorous, but in the slower frequency flash stimuli, it is higher amplitude and more prominent from the left compared to the right.

HR:  72 BPM, irregular.

IMPRESSION: Given the presence of an alpha asymmetry and the amplitude asymmetry, as well as the photic asymmetry, this is a mildly abnormal EEG due to:
1. The amplitude asymmetry comparing the left to the right and the slightly asymmetric photic stimulation.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record.  In this individual with a history of childhood head trauma, these findings should be correlated with imaging.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Given the presence of an alpha asymmetry and the amplitude asymmetry, as well as the photic asymmetry, this is a mildly abnormal EEG due to 1. The amplitude asymmetry comparing the left to the right and the slightly asymmetric photic stimulation.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 19-year-old male with possible posttraumatic epilepsy.  Patient has episodes when he falls asleep with of a feeling of hearing his blood rushing to the head with severe dizziness and tachycardia.  Last episode was this morning.  Patient states that he if catches it, he can stop it.  History of head trauma at age 6 with seizures, with last seizure at age 13.  This patient did experience another episode, as was seen in a previous EEG, with the feeling of tachycardia.
MEDICATIONS: None.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record. No clinical symptoms were reported during this EEG. The patient is known to have a right skull defect.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with an 11 Hz, 30 to 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. In wakefulness, there is a small intrahemispheric asymmetry with accentuation of fast activity in the right frontocentral region compared to the left.  This is compatible with a breach rhythm.  Features of drowsiness include slow rolling eye movements.  Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained.  During hyperventilation, the background EEG demonstrates an awake pattern with an increase in the amplitude and a small increase in theta.  Notably, in hyperventilation, the heart rate increases from 70 to 90 BPM.  The patient reports experiencing the typical symptoms of one of his events.
Photic stimulation is remarkable for a driving response.  The patient’s breach rhythm is somewhat more prominent during photic.
HR:  70 to 90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In view of the breach rhythm, which is a manifestation of a previous skull defect, the amplitude asymmetries and the beta asymmetries are anticipated findings.  As was seen in a previous EEG, the patient again felt tachycardic during hyperventilation and again demonstrated an increase in heart rate.
Additional, neurocardiac monitoring may be helpful to further characterize his spells.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 62-year-old male with hypothyroidism, benign prostatic hypertrophy, and carpal tunnel syndrome bilaterally who presents with an episode of syncope and inability to communicate several minutes afterwards, but is able to comprehend.
MEDICATIONS: Synthroid, Cardura, aspirin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: There is an 8.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm.  Throughout the record, there is unusual eye movement artifact, with very high amplitude eye artifact and somewhat asymmetric eye movements. These movements are lower amplitude on the right side, notably at the F8 lead.  The activity from the left temporal area also seems to be of greater amplitude.  There is also a suspicion of delta activity at F7 to T3.  Features of drowsiness include wicket activity, slow rolling eye movements, and an increase in beta.  Vertex waves are seen in stage I sleep.  Hyperventilation produces an increase in the amplitude of the background.   Photic stimulation elicits minimal driving.
HR:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
The presence of delta in the left frontotemporal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In view of the asymmetric eye movement artifact described above, this EEG should be repeated capturing stage II sleep.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to The presence of delta in the left frontotemporal region.

report:

report:
HISTORY:

60 y.o. FEMALE WITH  RECURRENT SZS.

PMHX:CVA.  SZ VS NON EPILEPTIC 59 CM HEAD




MEDICATIONS:


TOPAMAX


SEDATION: None



TECHNIQUE:

A 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the


International 10-20 system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a

NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record and

included a single channel of EKG and photic stimulation.






EEG BACKGROUND:

The waking background is symmetric, reactive, and consists of a


mixture of alpha and a moderate amount of bifrontal beta

activity, organized in a normal anterior-to-posterior gradient.


Wakefulness is characterized by a symmetric and reactive 9 Hertz

posterior dominant rhythm (PDR), which attenuates symmetrically

with eye opening.



During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and

fragmentation of the posterior dominant rhythm, and diffuse


background slowing are seen.


Sleep is characterized by normal sleep transients, with

synchronous and symmetric vertex waves, sleep spindles and


K-complexes. Slow wave sleep was not captured.



No generalized slowing is present.  No focal slowing is present.


EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:

No epileptiform activity is present.



OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):


None


ACTIVATION PROCEDURES: Hyperventilation and photic stimulation

are not performed.



Hyperventilation: Hyperventilation is not performed.



Photic Stimulation: Stepped photic stimulation is performed

and produces no effect.



EVENTS:

There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during


this study.



HEART RATE:

A heart rate of 90 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:
A 44-year-old left-handed male with 3 tonoclonic
seizures characterized by focal twitching, left arm shaking and then tonoclonic activity.
MEDICATIONS: 	Dilantin, insulin, others.
INTRODUCTION: 	Digital video EEG is performed in lab using 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION  OF THE RECORD: 	Background EEG in wakefulness is somewhat slow with excess background theta. Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record producing bursts of frontally predominant slowing; however, some of this is irregular with more irregular, sharply contoured signs on the right hemisphere with bursts lasting up to 5 seconds. The drowsy pattern demonstrates an increase in background slowing. In addition, more rhythmic, right frontal delta with suspicious underlying right frontal sharp waves are seen in brief bursts in the transition to drowsiness. Photic stimulation elicits
both photoelectric artifact and some driving.
HR: 	100 BPM.
IMPRESSION: 	Abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Generalized background slowing.
2. 	Superimposed bursts of paroxysmal frontal delta much more prominent from the right hemisphere with an underlying right frontal sharp wave.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a localization related mechanism for epilepsy. The focal findings may be correlated with imaging.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.Generalized background slowing. 2. Superimposed bursts of paroxysmal frontal delta much more prominent from the right hemisphere with an underlying right frontal sharp wave.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 	45 year-old gentleman with brain surgery for resection of tumor on the right, status post radiation now with 1-2 seizures per month, tonic, clonic with left focal facial twitching, left arm shaking then generalized tonic clonic activity with confusion.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Lipitor, Ativan.
INTRODUCTION:   Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. A right craniotomy defect is observed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9 hertz, symmetric active alpha rhythm. There is an amplitude asymmetry with higher amplitude activity on the right compared to the left. The patient drops into drowsiness with rhythmic theta
followed by vertex waves. Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record, but the
patient seems to be a bit drowsy. Immediately after hyperventilation, he drifts into stage
2 sleep with spontaneous K complexes and spindles. POST are observed. Although he has a stout neck, there is little in the way of snore artifact observed. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR: 	78 bpm
IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:   Despite the craniotomy defect and the history of ongoing epilepsy, there are no focal nor epileptiform features observed. Additional evaluation looking for possible causes of his seizures is advised.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 	This was a 35-year-old, right handed female, health care worker with new onset of episodes of generalized shaking. The patient could feel her body shake at the beginning of the episodes. Afterwards, she felt quite drained and had diffuse body soreness. The patient's typical seizures involved head turning and body twisting to the right. The patient may experience black spots in her eyes before the spells.
MEDICATIONS: 	Ativan.
INTRODUCTION: 	Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using the standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation  and photic stimulation were completed. The patient experienced one of her typical spells during the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: 	In wakefulness, there was a generous amount of background beta and a small of background theta. Hyperventilation was performed early on in the record producing increase in theta.
Following hyperventilation,  the patient began to have an episode of eye fluttering. The eye flutter began at 11:10:17. This gradually moved on towards one of her typical spells. The spell began at 11:10:35. The patient arched her back, stiffened and demonstrated generalized shaking. The spell was over by 11:11:11 so the total duration was approximately 40 seconds. No post
ictal slowing was identified. The patient recalled that the tech asked her a word but did not recall what the word was. Photic stimulation did not activate the record.
HR: 84   BPM.
IMPRESSION: 	Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Excess beta.
2. Mild excess theta.
. '
3. Behavioral event without clear EEG change and without post ictal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: 	The absence of an EEG signature as well as the absence of a post ictal state raised concerns that the behaviors recorded were not ictal in nature.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Excess beta. 2. Mild excess theta. . '
3. Behavioral event without clear EEG change and without post ictal slowing.

report:
History:	43 year old woman with a history of seizures since 2007.
Medications:	NEURONTIN,PRAZOSIN,PROZAC,BENADRYL KEPPRA,
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a very low voltage 10.5 Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Slow alpha rhythm is frequency seen.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-
25Hz activity is present, maximal over bilateral frontal regions.  Diffuse excess beta activity is
observed.  During brief drowsiness, the alpha rhythm attenuates, and 5-7Hz slow waves appear
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces no effect.
Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces symmetric photic driving at
multiple flash rates.
Summary of Findings:
No stage 2 sleep
Beta, excessive
No epileptiform discharges
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 22-minute EEG, awake and drowsy.  No epileptiform discharges were present,
but stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may
provide additional information. Excessive beta activity could be secondary to the medication effect,
such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL 22-minute EEG, awake and drowsy.  No epileptiform discharges were present,
but stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may
provide additional information. Excessive beta activity could be secondary to the medication effect,
such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 	18-year-old with childhood seizures characterized by absence seizures, positive family history of epilepsy. Patient was taken off Depakote a year ago because she was seizure free and had an event over the weekend with loss of awareness, falling. She recalls being confused for one-half hour to an hour afterwards.
MEDICATIONS: 	Depakote
INTRODUCTION: 	Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: 	In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm, but the overall background is disorganized and irregular. In the awake background, there is some subtle asymmetry with a bit more arrhythmic delta activity observed from the right in comparison to the left. There is also an underlying sharp wave focus seen subtly in the background in the right posterior temporal/parietal region.
Features of drowsiness including increase in background slowing. There is some rhythmic slowing observed in drowsiness. In addition, some of the focality is accentuated in drowsiness. Photic stimulation elicits bursts of rhythmic, high amplitude frontal delta as well as some occipitally predominant delta. Photic stimulation does elicit a bilateral driving response.
HR: 84 bpm
IMPRESSION: 	Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Background disorganization and an irregular pattern.
2. Subtle, underlying arrhythmic slowing from the right posterior quadrant with likely associated underlying sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: 	The background slowing and disorganization is nonspecific and supports a diffuse
disturbance of cerebral function. The epileptiform features were subtle. They may be better identified by additional sleep recording.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Background disorganization and an irregular pattern. 2. Subtle, underlying arrhythmic slowing from the right posterior quadrant with likely associated underlying sharp waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:   53-year-old right-handed  female, with left-sided weakness, aphasia, twitching and headache, fever, herpes encephalitis
MEDICATIONS:   Motrin, Ativan, Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement  with 1 channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, background  EEG demonstrates an interhemispheric asymmetry. The left hemisphere is appropriately  organized with 9 Hz 50 mV posterior dominant rhythm. The right hemisphere  is characterized  by intermittent arrhythmic delta. Although, much of the faster frequency activity persists with periodic, right centrotemporal sharp waves with a field of spread essentially throughout the entire right hemisphere. These vary in terms of the periodicity, but do not evolve to seizures. If the patient becomes drowsy, they become lower amplitude with more a pattern of sharply contoured delta. Deeper stages of sleep are characterized  by an increase in beta frequency activity. The patient is easily
stimulated with an awake pattern from the left and a periodic sharply contoured  slowing from the
right.
HR: 	96 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal electroencephalogram:
1. 	Right-sided focal slowing.
2. 	Periodic, high-amplitude  right temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORR ELATION:
This EEG supports a structural abnormality  on the right involving
gray and white matter. The periodic sharp waves support cortical irritability. This is a highly irritative pattern that raises concerns for ongoing seizures.  These results were reviewed with clinical team on 10/12/2007.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal electroencephalogram 1. Right-sided focal slowing. 2. Periodic, high-amplitude  right temporal sharp waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:   53-year-old woman now more than 1 week status post presentation for herpes encephalitis. This is a bedside portable in the ICU.
MEDICATIONS:   Heparin, Zofran, Nexium, Depacon, Solu-Medrol, Acyclovir
INTRODUCTION:   Digital video EEG is performed at bedside in the ICU using the standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Much of the records includes significant muscle movement artifact. The interpretable portions of the record demonstrate  an abnormal background with bursts of rhythmic delta observed bilaterally and a glimpse of a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm. There is more delta from the right compared to the left. There is another generous field in the right temporal region both anterior and posterior. Despite the muscle movement artifact, the patient was clearly more alert than on previous occasions and was moving about.
HR: 	60 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Technically limited, but abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Background slowing, bilaterally.
2. 	Intermittent rhythmic and arrhythmic delta activity from either hemisphere.
3.	Right greater than left rhythmic delta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:   The periodic activity has improved on the right in comparison to previous studies. There are no seizures, no PLEDS, and no focal spikes. A follow-up study when the patient is better able to cooperate is advised.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Technically limited, but abnormal EEG due to 1.Background slowing, bilaterally. 2. Intermittent rhythmic and arrhythmic delta activity from either hemisphere. 3.Right greater than left rhythmic delta.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 78-year-old gentlemen with tonic clonic admitted on 18th with tonic clonic
seizures responsive to 5 mg with Ativan and 5 mg of morphine but right facial twitching. The
patient was then loaded again with 3 mg of Ativan and Dilantin. Evaluate for subclinical status
epilepticus.
MEDICATIONS: Ativan, Dilantin, Heparin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of
electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE As the tracing opens, the patient is relatively lethargic, but
over the course of this postictal EEG, the patient is more arousable. The initial background is
low voltage, diffusely slow, but there are intermittent arousals with approximately 8 Hertz alpha
rhythm identified bilaterally right better than left. The patient waxes and wanes with some
portions of the records which are reasonably well organized with alpha and theta activity, other
which are low voltage featureless delta and others which are a mix of irregular mixed theta and
delta. Activity is slightly higher on the right. Through the course of the record, intermittent
attenuations are observed and there is a fair amount of waxing and waning although the close -
of the record does seem to be better then the beginning. There is some sharp slowing observed
in the right mid to anterior temporal region with an after going slow wave observed.
HR: 84 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Generalized background slowing.
2. Superimposed focal slowing with disruption of fast frequency on the left relative to the right.
3. Intermittent background attenuation.
4. Rare sharp wave observed on the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function
effecting both hemispheres perhaps more significantly on the left than the right. The sharp
waves, however, were on the right. No previous EEG were available for comparison.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Generalized background slowing. 2. Superimposed focal slowing with disruption of fast frequency on the left relative to the right. 3. Intermittent background attenuation. 4. Rare sharp wave observed on the right.

report:

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using the standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
stimulation are completed. The patient has prominent craniotomy scars in the right
central and temporal region.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is a 9.8 Hz alpha rhythm. A
breach rhythm is identified on the right with higher amplitude beta activity in that region and very subtle low voltage delta in the right centrotemporal region. Prominent wicket is noted in relaxed wakefulness. Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record, producing an increase in the amplitude, accentuating the breach rhythm and to a slight extent the focal slowing in the right centrotemporal region. Features of drowsiness
included an increase in amplitude of the background, a small amount of wicket, and again, a slight accentuation of the focal slowing in the right centrotemporal region. Deeper stages of sleep include stage I sleep with bilateral vertex waves. Photic stimulation produces bilateral driving.

HR: 84 bpm.

IMPRESSION: Markedly improved EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness due to:
1. Now a normal pattern on the left.
2. Intermittent focal slowing in the right centrotemporal region.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: A breach rhythm is an anticipated finding following
craniotomy. The focal slowing is in the region of his previous neurosurgery.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Markedly improved EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness due to 1. Now a normal pattern on the left. 2. Intermittent focal slowing in the right centrotemporal region.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  60 year old male status post a right left MCA stroke and right subdural hematoma with recurrent status epilepticus, focal motor and generalized tonic? clonic seizures earlier today.

MEDICATIONS: Keppra,  Dilantin, Trileptal, ASA, Lisinopril, Vit-B, Zocor


INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel  EKG. Patient is somnolent but moving about and answering questions.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG demonstrates a slow pattern bilaterally with theta-delta pattern.  In addition, superimposed upon this is a rhythmic delta from the right posterior quadrant and in this region there is also a sharp wave in the right posterotemporal region.

The patient has a seizure while working with the tech. The seizure seems to begin while the tech is working with the patient and the first ictal changes are at 15:48. The ictal changes include an increase in theta frequency activity.

By 01:49:00 very clear ictal changes are noted with the patient looking, instead of at the right, he is looking at the left and blinking. He remains responsive to the technologist at
0:48:55 as this activity builds up.  He seems to be confused, but he does follow commands and closes his eyes at 0:49:14. The tech is working with the patient so she does not observe the rhythmic repetitive theta activity in the right temporal region which spreads to the parietal and occipital region as well. He stops speaking, though.  By
15:50 the physician comes to examine the patient who is clearly confused and unable to follow commands, with roving eye movements.   He does provide a few words at
15:50:33. This electrographic seizure has a clear end at 15:51:11 and likely onset gradual evolution of faster frequencies at 15:48 for a total seizure duration of approximately 3 minutes.

Afterwards, the EEG returns to its previous, slower periodic sharp wave from the right hemisphere which gradually build up at 15:54:03.   Facial twitching is noted.

The second seizure is a grand mal seizure but starts with facial twitching and actually has a complex partial component where the patient actually seems to be somewhat

responsive and uncomfortable with focal and then asynchronous twitching. The second seizure is significantly longer in duration.  The tonic-clonic section of it is still relatively prolonged and is at least4  seconds in duration.

After the second seizure which has the tonic-clonic components, the overall EEG is quite slow but the periodic complexes in the right posterior quadrant persist.

HR:	150  bpm


IMPRESSION: Normal bedside EEG due to:
1. 	Tonic-clonic seizure.
2. 	Complex partial seizure.
3 .	Continuous right posterior quadrant periodic complexes.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal bedside EEG due to 1. Tonic-clonic seizure

IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to 1. Intermittent background  slowing. 2. Superimposed focal slowing with attenuation of faster frequency activity on the right, particularly in drowsiness.

report:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 27-year-old male with Dandy-Walker syndrome, cerebral palsy, and multiple shunts.
MEDICATIONS:  Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION:  A 20-minute digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed.  Although, there were multiple craniotomy defects, the patient was reasonably cooperative.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The EEG demonstrates a pattern of diffuse beta with prominent 9-10 Hz activity noted in the right frontal region, one of the noted craniotomy defects. Prominent eye movement artifact was seen.  The drowsy pattern is similar to the awake pattern with generous beta.
Photic stimulation did not activate the record. Heart rate: 132 BPM.
IMPRESSION: This EEG is remarkable for;
Absence of the normal awake morphologies for an adult of this age.
Diffuse generalized beta pattern.
Paroxysmal rhythmic right frontal alpha frequency activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There are no previous EEGs for comparison. This EEG supports a bihemispheric diffuse process.  The frontal alpha activity may be an epileptiform signature.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION: This EEG is remarkable for;
Absence of the normal awake morphologies for an adult of this age. Diffuse generalized beta pattern. Paroxysmal rhythmic right frontal alpha frequency activity.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 84 year old female with hypertensive with multiple syncopal episodes in the last few weeks to months.
MEDICATIONS: Pravastatin,  ASA, HCTZ
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. This is an awake and sleep study.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  During wakefulness, there is a disorganized background. The posterior dominant rhythm reaches at the start 6 Hz and up to 35 microvolts. As the record continues and patient reaches maximal wakefulness during stimulation, the background rhythm reaches at its maximum 9 Hz. There is an interhemispheric asymmetry seen with some focal slowing of the right hemisphere.  Sleep is seen with vertex waves and spindles and a little epochs of sleep, where the patient quickly awakens.  Hyperventilation accentuates the focal slowing in the right hemisphere.  Photic stimulation shows some scant driving, which is seen a bit better on the right posterior hemisphere.
HR:  66 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Generalized slowing of the background, which does reach 9 Hz, but the majority of the background is slow.
2. 	More focal slowing seen in the right hemisphere.
Scant driving seen asymmetrically  and better in the right posterior region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There is no epileptiform activity seen in this record. The generalized slowing of the background is nonspecific.  Initially, the focal slowing is seen in the right hemisphere,  but the driving is actually better in the right hemisphere,  which is incongruent and not initially expected.  The focal differences could be secondary to a structural abnormality and could get imaging this patient.  Clinical correlation is recommended.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.Generalized slowing of the background, which does reach 9 Hz, but the majority of the background is slow. 2. More focal slowing seen in the right hemisphere. Scant driving seen asymmetrically  and better in the right posterior region.

report:
REASON FOR STUDY:  Change in mental status.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 54-year-old woman with change in mental status and recent seizures with a history of epilepsy, schizophrenia, EPOC, and left mesial temporal sclerosis.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra and Depakote.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  The EKG electrode does not show a very good rhythm, a very low amplitude rhythm.  In addition, the impedances on the occipital electrodes and the right frontal and central electrodes were very high due to difficulty with the patient.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a recording that is mainly in sleep.  The patient is aroused at one point during the study and there appears to be a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 8 Hz, mainly seen over the right hemisphere, but for a short duration, again in the setting of electrode with a high impedance.  Overall the record is recorded during stage I and stage II and the first stages of sleep.  The patient falls asleep fairly quickly throughout this study.
Heart rate:  78 and appears to be regular.
Abnormal discharges:
Focal slow waves seen frequently at F7/T3 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-50 mV, at times with a very sharply contoured component.  Sometimes they appear to become rhythmic, but not clearly evolved or become continuous.
Focal slowing seen intermittently at T4 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-60 mV.
Mild excessive theta in wakefulness and limited wakefulness.
Seizures:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to left anterior temporal focal slowing, as well as right mid temporal focal slowing and mild excessive theta in limited wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG in limited wakefulness reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left anterior temporal region and independently in the right mid temporal region, both of which are nonspecific in regards to etiology.  In addition, the patient appears to have some mild diffuse generalized dysfunction, which is also nonspecific in regard to etiology.  No seizures or clear epileptiform discharges were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to left anterior temporal focal slowing, as well as right mid temporal focal slowing and mild excessive theta in limited wakefulness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 55-year-old woman with schizophrenia, epilepsy with tonic-clonic seizures, and recurrent hospitalizations for status epilepticus.  Currently, seizure-free for nearly 2 months.
MEDICATIONS:  Phenytoin.
INTRODUCTION:  A 20-minute digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.  There is some electrode placement issues with this EEG, but it is technically acceptable.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, the background EEG is very low voltage with a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm.  Stage II sleep includes vertex waves and spindles.
Photic stimulation elicited bilateral driving.
There is significant muscle twitch artifact noted in the background.
Heart rate 72 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness and brief sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is one of many EEGs for this adult with a history of refractory epilepsy.  No epileptiform features were noted today, but complex epileptiform activity has been noted with many different patterns over the past 4 years.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness and brief sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 59-year-old male with increasing frequency of visual spells where he feels like he is losing his visual perception and becoming blind, history of sarcoid and posterior retinal detachment.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Dilantin, and Solu-Medrol,
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.
Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is a technically acceptable record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG demonstrates an unusual pattern.  There is a slow alpha rhythm of approximately 6 hertz.  Intermittently, in the occipital region, there is fast activity of 14 hertz.  There appears to be a subtle asymmetry with a bit more vigorous 14 hertz activity in the left occipital region relative to the right and some subtle underlying occipital slowing noted on the right.  The patient is quite drowsy, transitioning from wakefulness to sleep.  In sleep, there are some POSTS noted, right more so than the left.
Photic stimulation was performed when the patient was drifting off to sleep, and no driving response was noted.
HEART RATE 90 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG for an adult due to:
Slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm.
An unusual pattern with beta activity noted in the occipital regions which seems to be asymmetric more so on the left than the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This patient's previous EEGs are not available for comparison.  No definitive epileptiform features were noted, but some of the findings noted today may be similar to previous occipital findings for this individual.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG for an adult due to Slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm. An unusual pattern with beta activity noted in the occipital regions which seems to be asymmetric more so on the left than the right.

depth perception.

EEG Type:	Awake & asleep
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Fast alpha variant is captured.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz
activity is present, maximal over bilateral frontal regions.  Diffuse excess beta is noted.  During
drowsiness, the background slows to central theta activity, frontal beta activity becomes more
prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes intermittent.  During stage 2 sleep, the
record slows further to moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric sleep spindles and K
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps)
does not produce any effect.
Summary of Findings:
Sleep, stage 2
Beta, excessive
No epileptiform discharges
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 22-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. The lack of epileptiform discharges
on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.  Excessive beta activity could
be secondary to the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 66 year old woman with a history of syncope, versus seizures dating to 2007, subsequently described as having cognitive impairment and seizures, history of COPD, obstructive sleep apnea and pneumonia.
MEDICATIONS: Vancomycin, Cefepime, Azithromycin, ASA
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximal wakefulness, there are some sections of the record with a 9.5 hertz posterior dominant rhythm, but other demonstrates a pattern of subtle, background slowing. At that point, the alpha rhythm slows to 8.3 hertz. Features of drowsiness include an increase in background slowing. The drowsy pattern differs from the relaxed wakeful pattern in that there are slow rolling eye movements.
HR: 110 bpm
IMPRESSION: Very mildly abnormal EEG due to:
1. Intermittent background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The background slowing is less remarkable than previous studies. Of note, this is the 4th EEG for this patient and to date none have demonstrated epileptiform activity. If seizures or syncope are frequent, a prolonged outpatient monitoring evaluation may be valuable.

INTRODUCTION:
An EEG is performed using standard the 10-20 electrode placement system with an EKG electrode. Awake and stage I sleep is recorded. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were used.
MEDICATIONS:
Vimpat and Tegretol.
TECHNICAL PROBLEMS:
None.
HISTORY:
A 37-year-old female who presents for followup EEG with past medical history significant for generalized epilepsy. Last seizure was reported in February 2011, with fall and loss of consciousness with urinary incontinence and postictal confusion lasting for an hour.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:
Posterior dominant alpha rhythm is seen at 9 to 10Hz frequency and 20 microvolt amplitude which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening. Frontocentral beta rhythm is also seen. Stage I sleep is seen and is normal. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed, which are also normal.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Generalized spike and wave at 4 to 4.5 Hz and 70 to 100 microvolts amplitude is seen, which is located maximum anteriorly. This generalized pattern is asymmetric with slight predominance in the left hemisphere. No seizures are seen.
IMPRESSION:
This is an abnormal EEG due to generalized spike and wave.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:
The EEG findings can be seen in generalized epilepsy; however, a sight asymmetric pattern raises the possibility of a focal epilepsy with secondary bilateral synchrony.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION This is an abnormal EEG due to generalized spike and wave.

There is a slight amplitude asymmetry and on one occasion a slight attenuation of overall background. These may be correlated with imaging.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 18 year old right handed woman with a first ever tonic clonic seizure. This seizure began with staring followed by tonic clonic activity, incontinence and 30 minutes of postictal confusion.
MEDICATIONS: None.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The initial sections of much of the waking record unfortunately includes head rocking artifact in the posterior regions. There is a 10.5 hertz alpha rhythm which is higher amplitude on the right than the left and posterior activity is always higher amplitude on the right than the left in this individual. Brief stage II sleep includes vertex waves, spindles and POSTS. Photic stimulation elicits a driving response, but the driving response is somewhat asymmetric, more vigorous on the left compared to the right. In addition, there is also a suggestion of a subharmonic driving response elicited on the left more so than the right.
HR: 66 bpm
IMPRESSION: Equivocally abnormal EEG due to:
1. Asymmetric photic stimulation described above.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The head rocking artifact is in the same region as the area of potential abnormality. A somewhat asymmetric photic stimulation is not necessarily pathological and some of the features that this patient demonstrated are compatible with normal variant. To more completely evaluate her epilepsy, a follow up study with more extended sleep is suggested.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Equivocally abnormal EEG due to 1. Asymmetric photic stimulation described above.

report:

MEDICATIONS: Carbatrol, Keppra, Topiramate.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is relatively low voltage with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. It is difficult to define an alpha rhythm in this background. Hyperventilation is performed with good effort producing an increase in amplitude of the background. Drowsiness is characterized by the appearance of lower voltage theta and delta. As the patient drifts into sleep in this low voltage record, some of the delta appears to be a bit more prominent in the left hemisphere. Photic stimulation elicits scan driving in this low voltage record.

HR: 60 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Replacement of normal background with more of a low voltage beta frequency pattern.
2. Focal slowing from the left hemisphere.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified today. In this low voltage record, the presence of the focal slowing on the left relevant to the right correlates with the previous craniotomy and neuropathology. No epileptiform activity seen since 2003.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Replacement of normal background with more of a low voltage beta frequency pattern. 2. Focal slowing from the left hemisphere.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 51-year-old, right-handed gentleman with history of aneurysm clipping, with history of seizures.  The patient has been seizure free for 5 years.

MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Topamax.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background activity was characterized by absence of a clear posterior dominant rhythm and a very low amplitude voltage recording.  There is a diffuse beta activity seen throughout the recording.  Stage 1 sleep is characterized by disappearance of a muscle and eye blink artifact and the presence of vertex sharp waves.  Stage 2 sleep is characterized by the presence of K complexes and sleep spindles.  Activating procedures produced no abnormal discharges.  Some focal slow waves are noted at anterior, temporal, and central area on the left side with some increase in faster frequencies at times.

IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to left frontocentral slowing.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left frontocentral region, which is consistent with the known surgery.  The absence of a normal posterior dominant rhythm, although atypical could be a normal variant.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to left frontocentral slowing.

aneurysm clipping several years ago. Pt has been seizure free over 5 years, now
presenting with mood swings.

EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
The background consists of very low voltage fast activity without clear AP gradient.  Patient remains
awake throughout the recording.
Subtle intermittent moderate amplitude polymorphic delta activity is captured over the left anterior
quadrant.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces no effect.
Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) does not produce any effect.
Summary of Findings:
Low voltage, severe
Beta, continuous diffuse
Focal slowing, polymorphic, intermittent, moderate, left anterior
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL awake-only 21-minute EEG due to subtle intermittent focal left anterior
moderate slowing. This finding is indicative of focal cerebral dysfunction, which is etiologically
non-specific, but possibly structural in origin.  When compared to prior EEGs, left anterior focal
slowing has been previously reported.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is an ABNORMAL awake-only 21-minute EEG due to subtle intermittent focal left anterior
moderate slowing. This finding is indicative of focal cerebral dysfunction, which is etiologically
non-specific, but possibly structural in origin.  When compared to prior EEGs, left anterior focal
slowing has been previously reported

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 23 year old male with new onset seizures.
MEDICATIONS: None
INTRODUCTION: Continuous digital video EEG was preformed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient keeps a log. He is able to push the button for all of the events that he experiences. He has multiple episodes of dizziness or disorienting feeling.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10 hertz posterior dominant rhythm which is symmetrically reactive. Drowsiness is characterized by rhythmic background theta with vertex waves, spindles and stage II sleep. There is an epoch in which REM sleep is seen.
In the interictal EEG, there is a single left temporal sharp wave.
Events: The patient has multiple dizzy spells including 129, 125, 312, 336, 536, 546 and then there are no additional push buttons noted.
Although not all of the seizures have a clear clinical correlate and some have only either subtle theta or subtle disruption of faster frequency activity in left temporal region, some have clear, rhythmic 4 hertz theta from the left temporal region with some spread to the frontocentral region bilaterally, typically lasting 20-40 seconds. The patient receives Depakote at 2:20p.m., the discharges are briefer, more evanescent more allusive.
Event time 12930: the patient has a dizzy spell characterized by decreased alpha frequency activity from the left temporal region and a brief burst of left temporal theta.
Event time: 2:32 p.m.: There is a brief burst of left temporal theta which differs from the background.
Event time: 3:12p.m.: Aura of dizziness, left temporal theta.
Event #3: Aura characterized by dizziness time 335 to 33729, rhythmic temporal theta as described above.
Event #4: Subtle left temporal theta at 3:53:52.
Event #5: 536, very subtle left temporal theta.
Event #6: Aura 5:46:13, brief burst of left temporal theta.
HR: 100 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG monitoring due to:
1. Subtle, intermittent attenuation of alpha frequency activity in the left temporal region.
2. A handful of well defined auras characterized by rhythmic 4 hertz theta with clear frequency evolution. The characteristic seizure pattern for this patient includes attenuation of alpha in the region, then the theta and then some bilateral frontocentral spread.
3. Rare interictal findings including sharp waves in the left temporal region and sharply contoured theta. An example of this is at 4:35:37 a.m. on the morning of the second.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG is diagnostic of a localization related
mechanism for epilepsy. These findings were reviewed with the patient during the hospitalization.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG monitoring due to 1. Subtle, intermittent attenuation of alpha frequency activity in the left temporal region. 2. A handful of well defined auras characterized by rhythmic 4 hertz theta with clear frequency evolution. The characteristic seizure pattern for this patient includes attenuation of alpha in the region, then the theta and then some bilateral frontocentral spread. 3. Rare interictal findings including sharp waves in the left temporal region and sharply contoured theta. An example of this is at 4:35:37 a.m. on the morning of the second.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  45 year old man right handed with history of seizures as a child, now with recurrent seizures and concurrent insomnia, anxiety, depression and migraines.
MEDICATIONS:  Tegretol, Lamictal, Temazepam, Seroquel, Effexor, Letherezia (?)
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using the standard 10-20 system of electrode placement as well as anterotemporal electrodes and EKG electrodes.  The EEG was recorded with photic stimulation and hyperventilation was performed.  Sleep stage I and stage II were recorded.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Frequent bilateral temporalis muscle artifact seen during the recording.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm of 9 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is a normal amount of frontal central beta.  Sleep stage I and stage II is recorded.  Photic stimulation and hyperventilation presented no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
There are 2 short bursts of less than 400 milliseconds seen with left frontal predominant sharp waves and slow waves which appeared to have a bilateral component and distribution more consistent with fragment of general spike and wave, however, a focal left frontal spike cannot be excluded.
SEIZURES:   None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
1.  Left frontal asymmetric spike and wave discharges likely fragments of generalized spike and wave
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with evidence of cortical irritability which is suggestive of an idiopathic generalized epilepsy.  However, the slight asymmetry of the spike and wave fragments may also suggest a focal origin with secondary bilateral synchrony.  Clinical correlation is recommended.  No seizures were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to 1.  Left frontal asymmetric spike and wave discharges likely fragments of generalized spike and wave

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 47-year-old male with childhood epilepsy, seizures recurred in 2011 associated with anxiety and depression.
MEDICATIONS:  Temazepam, Celexa, lamotrigine, and carbamazepine.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab/bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is a routine 20 minute EEG with acceptable impedances.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  As the tracing begins, the patient is somewhat drowsy.  The patient transitions in and out of an awake state with a well-defined, 9.2 hertz, 30 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta.  Features of drowsiness include slow rolling eye movements.
Hyperventilation was performed early on in the record and serve to keep the patient awake as well as increasing the amplitude of the alpha rhythm.
Photic stimulation elicited scant driving response.
Brief, stage 2 sleep included some electrode artifacts, but spindles were identified.
Heart rate 72 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and brief sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  This is in contrast to a previous EEG, October 27, 2011, which identified 2 left frontal sharp waves/spikes.  If additional information is needed, a more prolonged sleep study may be of use.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and brief sleep.

There epileptogenic structural abnormality over the right frontocentral region.
These findings were conveyed to the primary team at the time of the record review.  Patient was subsequently  placed on continuous  EEG monitoring.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  60 year old right handed male with complex partial epilepsy described as a feeling of spinning, hot flashes with loss of consciousness, and bowel and bladder incontinence.  Past history of closed head injury.

MEDICATIONS:  None.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is relatively low voltage with generous beta and a 9 Hz alpha rhythm.  With testing the alpha improves to 10 Hz.  Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements.  Wicket is noted in relaxed wakefulness. Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record.  The patient is falling asleep during hyperventilation with vertex waves and spindles.  There are some normal variants, including small sharp spikes of sleep, but there is also some left temporal focal slowing.  The patient transitions in and out of stage II sleep.  Again, subtle left temporal focal slowing is noted.  Simple sharp waves, as are common in normal variants, are also noted in the left temporal region. These are again noted with photic stimulation.  The patient is once again falling asleep during photic stimulation.

HR:    60 bpm

IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Subtle left temporal focal slowing.
2. Left temporal sharp waves.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The left temporal sharp waves have a simple morphology as can be seen in a normal variant.  However, they occur in the context of focal slowing and are more suggestive of a focal mechanism for epilepsy.  In comparison to a previous EEG, both EEGs demonstrate some of the same normal variants and some of the same unique challenges.

DD:01/05/2012
DT:01/05/2012
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to 1. Subtle left temporal focal slowing. 2. Left temporal sharp waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 61-year-old gentleman with a 4-6-year history of seizures characterized by a feeling of spinning followed by hot flashes with loss of consciousness, incontinence of bowel and bladder, and postictal confusion.  Past history of closed head injury.  His last seizure was December 2012.

MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.


INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1-channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is relatively low voltage with 9.5 Hz alpha rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Temporal wicket was noted.  In addition, there is subtle, left temporal focal slowing which was accentuated by hyperventilation.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in beta followed by vertex waves.  The subtle focal slowing persists into stage I sleep.  Stage II sleep includes vertex waves and spindles.  Photic stimulation was performed while the patient was relatively drowsy or in stage II sleep.  No driving response was identified.

Heart rate:  60 BPM.

IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to subtle left temporal focal slowing.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No definitive sharp waves were seen in this EEG although left temporal sharp waves were noted in the 2 previous studies.  This EEG supports a structural or functional abnormality.  Of note, there was wicket and left temporal focal slowing and subtle underlying seizures may have been under recognized.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to subtle left temporal focal slowing.

RECORDING ENVIRONMENT: outpatient


EEG TYPE: 20-40 min, awake and asleep




HISTORY:

a 65 y.o. male with a history of seizures (has been seizure free) referred for routine
EEG for characterization of seizures.



MEDICATIONS:


Current Outpatient Prescriptions:

ALBUTEROL IN, Inhale  into the lungs.

levetiracetam (KEPPRA) 1,000 mg tablet, Take 1 tablet by mouth 2 times daily for 360 days.


aspirin 81 mg EC tablet, Take 81 mg by mouth daily.

albuterol (PROVENTIL) 2.5 mg /3 mL (0.083 %) nebulizer solution, Take 3 mLs by nebulization
every 4 hours as needed for Wheezing for up to 360 days.



SEDATION: None



TECHNIQUE:






A  Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20
system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record
and included a single channel of EKG and photic stimulation.




EEG BACKGROUND:

The waking background is symmetric, reactive, and consists of a mixture of alpha and a moderate
amount of bifrontal beta activity, organized in a normal anterior-to-posterior gradient.  Wakefulness is
characterized by a symmetric and reactive 8.5 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm (PDR), which
attenuates symmetrically with eye opening.




During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior
dominant rhythm, and diffuse background slowing are seen.



Sleep is characterized by normal sleep transients, with synchronous and symmetric vertex waves,
sleep spindles and K-complexes. Slow wave sleep was not captured.



No generalized slowing is present.  No focal slowing is present.



EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:

No epileptiform activity is present.



OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):

None



ACTIVATION PROCEDURES:



Hyperventilation: Hyperventilation is not performed.


Photic Stimulation: Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) does not produce
any EEG changes.




EVENTS:

There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.



HEART RATE:

A heart rate of 54 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.



IMPRESSION:




This is a normal awake and asleep routine EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic events
reported or detected.



CLINICAL CORRELATION:


This is a normal awake and asleep routine EEG.

A normal routine EEG does not support or refute the diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 



This is a normal awake and asleep routine EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic events
reported or detected.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  30 year old right handed male with new onset seizures characterized by sitting at work, saw stars and blacked out with convulsive activity, fell off the chair, tongue biting, postictal confusion.   History of bipolar disease, anxiety, and headaches.
MEDICATIONS:  Ativan, Seroquel, Doxepin, Lovenox.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  There was no photic stimulation nor hyperventilation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm.  There is a small amount of theta.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in beta.  Lateral rectus artifact is noted.
HR:    96 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Mildly abnormal EEG due to:
A small amount of theta.
Disorganization.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The findings described above are nonspecific.  They can be seen in a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function due to many different causes including postictal state or medication effect.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Mildly abnormal EEG due to A small amount of theta. Disorganization.

report:
HISTORY:  A 33-year-old male with 2-3 year history of epilepsy, perhaps, only 3-4 seizures in his life.  Most seizures began with an aura, but recent gastroenteritis with vomiting, could not keep down medicines and had a seizure without warning.  Was noted in the ER to have transient left-sided weakness.
MEDICINES:  Aspirin, Lovenox, Depakote, Topamax, and Seroquel.
INTRODUCTION:  1 hour digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is an awake record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Hyperventilation produces an increase in the frequency of the overall background.  Photic stimulation elicited bilateral driving.
Heart rate:  120 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were seen.  This is a third EEG without epileptiform features noted for this individual.  Of note, at least 1 study was a postictal study, which did identify some background slowing.  If additional information is needed, a more prolonged EEG may be of use.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  73 year old right handed woman with new-onset seizures and end-stage renal disease on hemodialysis.
MEDICATIONS:  Protonix, Hydralazine, Plavix, Metoprolol, ASA, Lipitor, Lisinopril.
REASON FOR STUDY:  New-onset seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and drowsiness.  Photic stimulation was performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with a posterior dominant rhythm that best reaches 7 Hz and which appears to be reactive to eye opening.  There is a lack of normal frontocentral beta.  No normal sleep architecture is seen.  Photic stimulation produces no abnormal discharges.  Throughout the recording, there appears to be diffuse generalized theta, 5 to 7 Hz discharge, that is intermixed with bursts of high-amplitude delta seen bilaterally with multiple sharp components throughout those discharges that last, at times, up to 30 to 40 seconds.  There is no clear evolution or change during these discharges.  The morphology is consistent with triphasic waves, but there are some intermixed sharp waves that we will discuss in "abnormal discharges" below.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal sharp waves seen independently at F7/T3, as well as F8/T4, and at times FP2.
Bursts of generalized slow waves at 2 to 4 Hz with an amplitude of 20 to 50 microvolts.
Triphasic waves.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Multifocal sharp waves.
Bursts of generalized slow waves.
Triphasics in the midst of moderate diffuse cerebral dysfunction.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of multiple focal cerebral irritability and dysfunction, in addition to diffuse cerebral dysfunction which may be, at least in part, due to a metabolic derangement.  No seizures were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Multifocal sharp waves. Bursts of generalized slow waves. Triphasics in the midst of moderate diffuse cerebral dysfunction.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  73 year old right handed female with rue twitching and change of mental status.
MEDICATIONS:  Zofran, Keppra, Lopressor, Metoprolol, Dilaudid, Zosyn, Dextrose, Glucose.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded while lethargic.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Some movement artifact throughout the recording.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with a posterior dominant rhythm that at best reaches 6 Hz, which is somewhat reactive to eye opening.  There is no normal frontocentral beta.  No normal sleep architecture is seen.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Generalized slow waves at 2 to 4 Hz seen continuously throughout the recording with an amplitude of 20 to 60 microvolts.  In addition, there are intermittent bursts of anterior predominant slowing at times with a triphasic morphology seen intermittently.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized slow waves.
Triphasics at 3-4 Hz with anterior predominance.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regard to etiology; however, the presence of triphasics suggests at least the possibility of a metabolic encephalopathy.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Generalized slow waves. Triphasics at 3-4 Hz with anterior predominance.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  21 year old right handed woman who presents with a 3-year history of complex partial seizures characterized by an aura of a strong smell, deja vu, and tunnel vision.  Her last seizure was 2 months ago.

MEDICATIONS:  Lamictal, Keppra.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is well organized, but there is an asymmetry of the alpha rhythm.  The alpha rhythm is 50 to 60 microvolts, approximately 10 Hz on the left and consistently 0.7 Hz faster on the right.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in amplitude of the background.  Hyperventilation produces bilateral slowing.  Wicket study was identified, but no sharp waves were noted.  Posterior slow waves of youth were noted. Photic stimulation elicited bilateral driving.

HR:    60 to 72 bpm and irregular.

IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
1. A slower alpha rhythm on the left.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The slower alpha on the left suggests pathology in that hemisphere.  No sharp waves were identified, although Wicket was noted.  A repeat study capturing deeper stages of sleep may be of value.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to 1. A slower alpha rhythm on the left.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 72-year-old woman with diabetes, acute onset stroke on the 6th, 3 week history of vertigo, numbness and weakness on the right.
MEDICATIONS:  Zofran, lisinopril, Levemir.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm.  There is a subtle asymmetry with a bit more slowing in the left hemisphere, some slowing of the alpha rhythm and some theta.  In addition, there are occasional bursts of shifting, arrhythmic mixed delta theta, and prominent fast activity in the frontal regions right or left.  Wicket activity was identified.

Photic stimulation elicits a bilateral driving response.
Heart:  64 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to:
Shifting slowing from the right or left hemisphere in relaxed wakefulness.
A subtle asymmetry with somewhat slower activity in the left hemisphere.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  Wicket activity was present.  A follow up study capturing deeper stages of sleep is suggested to exclude epileptiform activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to Shifting slowing from the right or left hemisphere in relaxed wakefulness. A subtle asymmetry with somewhat slower activity in the left hemisphere.

report:
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizure.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 34-year-old male with history of alcohol withdrawal seizure, was discharged, when he had a general tonic-clonic seizure.
MEDICATIONS:  Serax, thiamine, Lovenox, nicotine patch, folic acid.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches at 10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  The patient is recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Bursts of generalized spike and waves which is anterior predominant and symmetric, and bursts of 3-4 Hz were seen intermittently, at times with preceding polyspikes throughout the recording.  Some of them appeared more asymmetric on the right than the left, but the majority appear symmetric.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to generalized spike and waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with a diagnosis of epilepsy.  The discharges seen above are most commonly seen with a generalized type of epilepsy.  However, some of them appeared slightly asymmetric and may suggest a possible focal onset with secondary generalization.  Repeated EEG capturing seizures or clinical followup may aid in elucidating the clear classification.  These findings were reported to the consult team as soon as the EEG was read.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to generalized spike and waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 51 year old right handed female with left carotid stenosis and left CEA with a history of left stroke in June of 2012.
MEDICATIONS:  Propofol, Percocet, Fentanyl, Vecuronium, Isoflurane
REASON FOR STUDY:  Left carotid endarterectomy.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed during left carotid endarterectomy using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with the addition of anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during the entire operation.  Feedback was given to the surgeon as well as discussions with Anesthesia was had throughout the procedure.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The baseline record revealed a posterior dominant rhythm that reached 9-10 Hz which was reactive to eye opening.  At times there was some focal slowing seen at F7/T3 at 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.  Otherwise, there was nice frontocentral beta. During the procedure the common carotid was clamped at 10:32:36 and the internal carotid was clamped at 10:31:50.  After clamping no change in the faster frequencies over the left hemisphere were noted and this was informed to the surgeon at 3 and 5 minutes.  The recording continued to be monitored and there continued to be no change at 11:48:13 a.m.  The carotids were unclamped and again there was no change in the faster frequencies in the recording.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG consistent with symmetric background of 9 Hz with no change in the background upon carotid artery clamping.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This was an uneventful left carotid endarterectomy with no changes.  Feedback was given continuously to the surgeon about the EEG.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG consistent with symmetric background of 9 Hz with no change in the background upon carotid artery clamping.

report:
REASON FOR STUDY:  Change in mental status and seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 54-year-old female with history of mental illness, migraines, and seizures who presented to the hospital with 3 episodes of seizures described as tonic clonic and confusion after stopping her Xanax for 2 days.
MEDICATIONS:  Lorazepam, phenobarbital, Tylenol, vitamin B12.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with an additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient is recorded during wakefulness, drowsiness, and stage I sleep.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record reveals a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is an excessive amount of diffuse beta.  The patient is mainly in drowsiness or sleep, stage I.
Hyperventilation produces no abnormal discharges.
Abnormal discharges:
Focal slow waves seen intermittently at T3 and at times at T4 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-60 mV.
Excessive theta in wakefulness.
Seizures:  None.
Heart rate:  78 and regular.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to bilateral independent mid temporal slowing, as well as excessive theta in wakefulness with superimposed diffuse beta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the bilateral mid temporal regions, but of which are nonspecific with regards to etiology.  In addition, there was evidence of mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology, but may be due at least in part to medication effect.  The excess beta supports a possibility of benzo or barbiturate use as a cause of the diffuse dysfunction.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to bilateral independent mid temporal slowing, as well as excessive theta in wakefulness with superimposed diffuse beta.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 56-year-old man who presented with a chief complaint of left-sided numbness and shaking.  While in the emergency room he was observed having shaking while in the CAT scan.  Past medical history is notable for diabetes, hypertension and neuropathy.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Zolpidem, lisinopril, aspirin, insulin, and others.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were  performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORDING:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of well modulated low amplitude 10 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  No clear sleep is captured.  Intermittent polymorphic delta activity is captured over the right anterior temporal region.  Hyperventilation produces no change in the background.  Photic stimulation induces symmetric occipital driving at multiple flash frequencies.
FINDINGS:
Intermittent moderate right anterior temporal slowing.
No stage II sleep.
No epileptiform discharges.
IMPRESSION:  This is a mildly abnormal awake only, 24 minute EEG due to intermittent moderate anterior right temporal slowing.  This finding indicates underlying cerebral dysfunction and this case could be structural in etiology.  No epileptiform discharges are captured, however, stage II sleep was not recorded.  If clinical indication for seizures persistent a repeat study with stage II sleep may be of benefit.
