This finding indicates underlying cerebral dysfunction and this case could be structural in etiology.  No epileptiform discharges are captured, however, stage II sleep was not recorded.  If clinical indication for seizures persistent a repeat study with stage II sleep may be of benefit

report:
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 56-year-old man with a history of left-sided numbness and weakness and shaking and falling down stairs.  History of diabetes, hypertension, and neuropathy.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Altace, Ativan, and Oxycontin.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included photic stimulation and hyperventilation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a background, which appears to have diffuse beta and mainly in sleep.  There is no clear posterior dominant rhythm, but this may be obscured by the diffuse beta.  Overall, the patient easily drowses off and is in limited wakefulness.  During hyperventilation, there appears to be some bursts of rhythmic bifrontal slowing.  Photic stimulation produced no abnormal discharges.  The patient reaches stage I and stage II sleep.  Please note that at times there is also rhythmic bursts of theta, which are anterior maximal, which are most consistent with drowsiness, however, some of them have a slightly suspicious appearance.
SEIZURES:  None.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
HEART RATE:  78.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and asleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and asleep EEG.  The excessive beta seen may be due at least in part to medication effect.  Please note that even though no clear posterior dominant rhythm could be seen, this may be due to the excessive beta, and in addition, the rhythmic anterior theta is likely due to drowsiness, however, if clinical suspicion for epilepsy remains, a more prolonged EEG may be helpful in elucidating or clarifying the diagnosis.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and asleep EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 21-year-old woman with an unknown early developmental history, depression, and posttraumatic stress syndrome.  The patient has been having an episode to right arm rotation and had a seizure with loss of consciousness and incontinence.  She continues to feel, as if she is experiencing myoclonic jerks.  I got interrupted and I did not do the history.

MEDICATIONS: Lorazepam, Remeron

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  This is a bedside record without hyperventilation and photic stimulation.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there was a 10Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Drowsiness was characterized by an increase in beta.

In wakefulness, there were bursts of frontally predominant rhythmic high amplitude 3-5 Hz spike and wave activity.

No impairment of awareness was noted with the events.  The patient was able to answer questions even with very brief discharges, but again discharges are typically 1 to 1.5 seconds after going slow activity, lasting an another second at maximum duration.

The technologist notes 1 or 2 movements of the patient, but no definitive myoclonus was captured.

Heart rate 84 BPM.

IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
1. frontally predominant 3-5 Hz spike in wave activity occurring in brief bursts.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  For this young adult with unclear medical history and a 1st ever seizure and myoclonus, this EEG is most compatible with a inherited, generalized mechanism for epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to 1. frontally predominant 3-5 Hz spike in wave activity occurring in brief bursts.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 22-year-old woman with unknown early developmental history, posttraumatic stress syndrome, depression, past history of suicidal ideation, past history of involuntary jerking.  Now, patient reports headaches if she becomes anxious are associated with shaking, incontinence, or tongue biting every 2-4 weeks.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Trileptal, Xanax, Claritin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is an awake and asleep record.  It was a technically acceptable record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with an 11 Hz alpha rhythm and a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Mu rhythm was noted, but testing was not performed to confirm this.  Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements.  Deeper stages of sleep were not sustained.
Hyperventilation did not significantly activate the record.  Photic stimulation elicited bilateral driving with vigorous supra-harmonic driving.
Heart rate 72 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness and brief sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  In contrast to a previous EEG 2 years ago, there were no bursts of 3-5 Hz spike and wave activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  If this patient is thought to have frequent seizures, more prolonged EEG monitoring may be obtained.  These findings may be carefully correlated with clinical symptoms in this individual, whose previous EEG pattern suggested that she is at risk for myoclonic or tonic-clonic epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness and brief sleep.

disorganization. These findings are etiologically nonspecific indicators of mild diffuse cerebral
dysfunction.  A single EKG lead demonstrates heart rate of ~ 49 bpm.

Interpretation This is an ABNORMAL awake and asleep 28-minute EEG due to mild diffuse slowing and
disorganization. These findings are etiologically nonspecific indicators of mild diffuse cerebral
dysfunction.  A single EKG lead demonstrates heart rate of ~ 49 bpm

EVENTS:

A heart rate of 54 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.

This is a normal, albeit limited (near constant eye movement artifact during wakefulness), awake and
drowsy routine EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic events reported or detected.

This is a normal, though limited, awake and drowsy routine EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 28-year-old right-handed male who has a history of epilepsy since 2007, has about 1 seizure every 1-2 years, presently not on any medications.  Last seizure was several nights ago.  The seizure was preceded by a severe headache.

MEDICATIONS:  None.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.  There was a technical limitation with the T6 electrode which persisted even after it was fixed by the technician.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a posterior dominant rhythm of 9.5 Hz in frequency and 20-40 microvolts in amplitude best seen in the occipital region which attenuates with eye opening.  In drowsiness there is diffuse rhythmic theta bursts in all the channels.

There is an occasional burst of focal slowing seen in the left frontocentral region.

Hyperventilation was performed which showed a diffuse slowing of the record and increase in amplitude.

Photic stimulation showed minimal driving at 13 Hz but no abnormalities.

Heart rate 60 beats per minute.

IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to occasional bursts of focal slowing on the left frontocentral and frontotemporal regions.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is suggestive of a possible underlying structural abnormality in the left frontocentral and frontotemporal regions.  No epileptiform discharges were identified.  A more prolonged EEG recording may be more helpful to identify spikes or sharp waves.

Attestation: I personally reviewed the EEG with the trainee and agree with the report.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to occasional bursts of focal slowing on the left frontocentral and frontotemporal regions.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 53-year-old female, who was admitted for change in mental status.  She has a history of diabetes, hypertension, depression, and breast cancer.

MEDICATIONS:  Insulin, Haldol, lorazepam, labetalol, vancomycin, aztreonam, lisinopril.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  At 11:22:17 a.m., there is a seizure onset at 9-10 Hz alpha activity, maximum in left occipital region (01) with spread to left posterior quadrant and right occipital region, after 20 seconds seizure activity continues as 4-5 Hz theta activity maximum in left posterior quadrant for 40 seconds.  This activity was followed by sharply contoured delta activity with bihemispheric distribution for 90 seconds.  It was followed by postictal attenuation noted in bihemispheric region.  Clinically, patient did not show shaking or jerking, but per video patient seemed less responsive with eyes closed.  Towards the end of this recording, there were left periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges noted in left posterior quadrant region lasting for several minutes with no evolution. There was almost continuous left posterior quadrant slowing almost continuous noted during this recording.

IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to;
1. Electrographic partial seizure originating from left occipital/left posterior quadrant region.
2. Left posterior quadrant slowing.
3. Left periodic lateralized epileptiform

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Focal slowing is a consistent with functional or structural abnormality in left posterior quadrant. PLEDs (Periodic Lateralized Epileptiform Discharges) are consistent with left hemisphere structural lesion (tumor, infection, and stroke). It could also be due to a post-ictal state. One episode of electrographic focal seizure is consistent with partial epilepsy in the setting of Hx of seizure. Clinical correlation and long-term monitoring are recommended.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to;
1. Electrographic partial seizure originating from left occipital/left posterior quadrant region. 2. Left posterior quadrant slowing. 3. Left periodic lateralized epileptiform

report:
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 70-year-old woman with a right frontal craniotomy on July 6, 2012, and seizures a couple of days after and had surgery.
MEDICATIONS:  Lamictal, Cozaar, Lopid, Flonase, albuterol.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using a standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  Patient was recorded during wakefulness and drowsiness.  Activating procedure included photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is mild excessive beta seen diffusely.  the patient was recorded in wakefulness and drowsiness.
Activating procedures produced no abnormal discharges which included only photic stimulation.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal sharp waves seen at F8/F4 while in wakefulness and sleep.
Focal slow waves seen at F8/F4 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and amplitude of 20-50 microvolts.  There is an increased amplitude and presence of faster frequencies consistent with a breach rhythm in that region.
SEIZURES:  None.
HEART RATE:  Eighty-four.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal electroencephalogram due to right frontal slowing and sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with the diagnosis of  localization-related epilepsy with seizures likely arising from the right frontal region.  In addition, there is evidence focal cerebral dysfunction in the right frontal region consistent with the known surgery.   No seizures were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal electroencephalogram due to right frontal slowing and sharp waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 21-year-old woman with epilepsy since age 17, recent MVA.  Seizures previously described as tonic-clonic seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Pentasa, methotrexate, Celexa, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Impedances were acceptable, although T1 and T2 electrodes slightly greater than 5 kohms.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a low voltage, 11 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  In the initial sections of the record there is frequent eye blink, but there is also a subtle area of sharply contoured slowing in the right mid temporal region at T2 and T4.  Hyperventilation is performed slightly after this finding is noted and produces an increase in amplitude, an increase in beta and does not clearly accentuate this finding which is noted again as the patient becomes drowsy with slow rolling eye movements.  This subtle lower voltage focal slowing in the right mid to posterior temporal region has almost a periodicity and when there is some overlying alpha frequency activity there is appearance of a low voltage sharp but without an after going slow wave.  It persisted into drowsiness with an increase in beta but deeper stages of sleep were not achieved.
The patient was relatively drowsy during photic stimulation which did elicit a driving response.
Heart rate 60 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to right mid to posterior temporal focal slowing at times sharply contoured with a frequency of approximately 4 Hz.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These findings are very similar to the previous study 05/13/2013.  There is a slight periodicity of the focal slowing.  These findings contrast to previous EEGs in childhood which are reported to have demonstrated generalized spike and wave activity.  But these findings were similar on the previous study and therefore are not likely to have been associated with the car accident and concussion.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to right mid to posterior temporal focal slowing at times sharply contoured with a frequency of approximately 4 Hz.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 22-year-old young woman with seizures beginning in 2007 consisting of generalized tonic-clonic convulsions with tongue biting.  She has not had any recent seizure activity.  The study is done as a followup.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra
INTRODUCTION:  Routine 21-channel EEG was performed utilizing the standard 10-20 system of electrode placement along with hyperventilation and photic stimulation EKG and EOG monitoring.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The white cresting background reveals a large amount of 50-70 microvolt amplitude posterior alpha rhythm with a large amount of 18-30 Hz low voltage of her frontocentral regions.  Large amount of eye blink artifacts were seen throughout much of the waking record.  Moderate amount of muscle artifact was also seen.  With eye opening, there was attenuation of alpha activity.  Periods of drowsiness were seen with attenuation of posterior rhythmic activity and increased slow to medium amount due to symmetric irregular slowing.  Hyperventilation for 3 minutes produced mild increased low to medium amounts.  Bilateral delta and theta frequency slowing.  Photic stimulation was accompanied by symmetric occipital driving.  EKG monitor showed normal sinus rhythm at 60 per minute.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and drowsy EEG.  A normal EEG cannot exclude the clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.  If clinically indicated, a sleep deprived tracing capturing stage II sleep or more prolonged ambulatory EEG may provide additional information.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  19-year-old with and epilepsy since age 5 or 6.  Seizure free for 10 years until he had 2 breakthrough seizures over 2 days with loss of consciousness, tongue biting, postictal confusion.  Headaches precede the seizures.

MEDICATIONS:  None.

INTRODUCTION:  Routine 24-minute outpatient digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  Impedances were acceptable under 5 kilohms with the exception of the T1-T2 electrodes.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is abnormal.  At best, there is an 8 Hz alpha rhythm but there is excess background theta.  In addition, there are occasional bursts of background delta some of which are a bit more posteriorly predominant.  Hyperventilation was performed early in the record and accentuated this finding.  As the patient became drowsy after hyperventilation, there was some shifting arrhythmic slowing a bit more prominent in the posterior regions.  Deeper stages of sleep were not sustained.  Photic stimulation elicited scant driving.

HEART RATE:  40 BPM.

IMPRESSION:  This is a markedly abnormal EEG due to:
1. Marked background slowing.
2. Bursts of frontal slow delta.
3. Occasional shifting occipital slowing.
4. Bradycardia.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  To put this EEG in the proper context, it is important to know when this patient had his most recent seizures.  This may represent a postictal finding.  Comparison with previous EEGs is suggested.
The ordering physician will be contacted regarding the bradycardia.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is a markedly abnormal EEG due to 1. Marked background slowing. 2. Bursts of frontal slow delta. 3. Occasional shifting occipital slowing. 4. Bradycardia.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 22-year-old woman who was shoved 10 the floor on the 23rd, no loss of consciousness, but then had 2 episodes that were described as seizures. Previous, "minor" head injury without loss or consciousness.
MEDICATIONS: Depacon, Zofran, tramadol, others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed In lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode
placement with 1 channel EKG. Impedances were acceptable aside from the T1-T2 electrodes.
Electrode placement was perhaps suboptimal due to some or the features of the vertex waves.
DESCRIPTION OF THE As the tracing begins, the patient is asleep. Features of stage 1 and
stage 2 sleep are noted with vertex activity and spindles. Intermittent bursts of delta were noted. There
is prominent beta. There is a slight asymmetry noted with a bit of slowing noted on the left with a bit more
delta on the left relative to the right Eye movement and EKG artifacts as well were noted 10 the
background.

Hyperventilation was performed early in the record. Hyperventilation clearly accentuates focal slowing
from the left hemisphere, and in hyperventilation, discrete left temporal sharp waves emerge. As the
hyperventilation concludes, the patient drifts off back to sleep with generous beta and again focal slowing
noted from the left. In more prolonged stage II sleep, some of the vertex waves and spindles are slightly
asymmetric. Photic stimulation was performed while the patient was drifting off to sleep. II does not
significantly activate the record, but the focal sharp waves and focal slowing persist In sleep, there are
some lower voltage, discreet bilateral spikes noted with a bit of a field to the left.
At the close of the record, the patient is transitioning back into stage II sleep, but limited wakefulness was
identified with a symmetric brief posterior dominant rhythm.
Heart rate 60 bpm.
IMPRESSION: This is an abnormal EEG due to:
1. Focal stowing from the left temporal region.
2. Discrete fell temporal spikes.
3. A number of discrete, bifrontal spikes.
4. Hypersomnolence.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Th1s EEG supports a structural or functional process on the left with focal
epileptiform features These findings may be correlated with Imaging
This patients medications should also include Remeron and Abilify.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This is an abnormal EEG due to 1. Focal stowing from the left temporal region. 2. Discrete fell temporal spikes. 3. A number of discrete, bifrontal spikes. 4. Hypersomnolence.

Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes
Continuous bedside video-EEG monitoring
Continuous EEG monitoring was performed for ~18 hours from ~ 1 pm on 10/10/2013 till ~ 7 am on
10/11/2013.   Nursing-initiated event buttons were correlated with clinical behavior.  Ongoing raw
EEG data was reviewed at least twice daily by the EEG team for detection of seizures and changes
in EEG patterns.   All automatically detected events were reviewed in detail by the attending
neurologist.  The Gotman spike and seizure detection algorithm (Stellate) was used to screen the
EEG in real time for electrographic seizures and interictal epileptiform discharges.
# Push button events
Description of pushbutton events

Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates

recording and increases during drowsiness.  During drowsiness, the background slows to central
theta activity, frontal beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and

No electrographic seizures

excessively drowsy patient.  No electrographic seizures are present.  These findings were conveyed
to the primary team.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This 40-year-old left-handed woman with asthma, stroke, migraine headache, and seizures.  Patient had recurrent seizures, 1-2 days prior to admission with 2 seizures, and then 3 seizures on the day of admission with 1 hour postictal confusion.  The patient is on the 4th floor.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation was performed.  Photic stimulation was not completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG was somewhat slow and disorganized.  With a posterior dominant rhythm of 7 Hz, intermittent background theta was noted.  As the recording continues, the patient was stimulated and briefly a 9 Hz alpha rhythm emerges.  Hyperventilation was performed with good effort, serving to alert the patient, and a more normal pattern was identified.  Following hyperventilation, the patient drifts off into drowsiness.  There is a bit of irregular slowing in the right hemisphere particularly centrotemporal and centroparietal.
Posts were noted in stage 1 sleep.
Heart rate 60 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Technically challenging bedside record with some impedances greater than 5 kilohms, but abnormal due to paroxysmal slowing and apparent wakefulness in the context of a patient who seemed to be quite drowsy.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There were subtle focal features noted only on 1 section in this bedside record.  These findings may be correlated with imaging.  The background slowing is a nonspecific finding, but this paroxysmal pattern can be seen in a postictal pattern or in the context of a toxic or metabolic pattern.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Technically challenging bedside record with some impedances greater than 5 kilohms, but abnormal due to paroxysmal slowing and apparent wakefulness in the context of a patient who seemed to be quite drowsy.

International 10-20 system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a

NicOne system. This was a  technically satisfactory record and


included a single channel of EKG, HV and photic stimulation.  The

patient was drowsy or asleep for most of the record.


EEG BACKGROUND:

The waking background is symmetric, reactive, and consists of a

mixture of alpha and a moderate amount of bifrontal beta

activity, organized in a normal anterior-to-posterior gradient.


Wakefulness is characterized by a symmetric and reactive 9 Hertz

posterior dominant rhythm (PDR), which attenuates symmetrically


with eye opening.  When drowsy, the alpha slows to 7 Hz.



During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and

fragmentation of the posterior dominant rhythm, and diffuse


background slowing are seen.



Sleep is characterized by normal sleep transients, with

synchronous and symmetric vertex waves, sleep spindles and

K-complexes. Slow wave sleep was not captured.  Patient has EOMS

in stage II sleep.



No generalized slowing is present.  No focal slowing is present.



EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:

No epileptiform activity is present.



OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):

None

Hyperventilation: - patient falling asleep, slow background



Photic Stimulation: Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21


flashes per second (fps) induces symmetric photic driving, which

is a normal finding.

report:
HISTORY:

This is a 42 y.o. left handed female admitted for continuous video-electroencephalography (VEEG)
monitoring with a history of: paroxysmal events of unclear etiology.




Continuous video EEG is initiated for:  Evaluation of paroxysmal events.



Inpatient continuous EEG monitoring required due to one or more of the following reasons:

- The patient is having medically uncontrolled seizures or clinical events, which poses a significant
mortality and morbidity risk.  Continuous monitoring will aid in diagnosis and determining best
treatment options.  If seizures are left untreated, there is a 10-20% annual morbidity and 2% annual
mortality rate.



- Continuous monitoring is required to capture a sufficient number of clinical events or seizures, while
medication are reduced or provoked, which increases the risk of severe seizures and at risk of seizures
causing injury or status epilepticus;






- The EMU is set up to monitor and record EEGs during seizures and it includes nurses trained to
provide first aid and patient safety during seizures;


- The full hospital team must be present to deal with these medical emergency situations should they
arise, including nurses to document patients exam


(9) there have been 13 reported deaths during various video-EEG monitoring procedures, so this is
not a "low risk" service



CONDITIONS OF THE RECORDING:

A routine 21 channel digital EEG was recorded at the onset of monitoring.  The patient then
underwent continuous CCTV/EEG monitoring using a cable telemetry system.  Scalp electrodes were
placed and secured with collodion according to the 10-20 international electrode system.
Additionally, T1, F9, T9, P9, T2, F10, T10, and P10 electrodes were placed in this patient.
Sphenoidal electrodes were not used in this case.  Impedances were measured and verified to be
below 5 Kohms.  EEG activity was recorded referentially to vertex reference, digitized, and stored to
computer hard drive.  Periods of interest were subsequently reformatted to the montage of interest
and reviewed in detail.






Staff supervision, patient-initiated event buttons and computerized algorithms allowed detection of
epileptiform EEG activity and correlation with behavior.  For approximately 8 hours each day the
patient was attended by an EEG technician.  A neurologist was available in person or on call 24
hours per day.  The patient was monitored via video 24 hours per day by a registered nurse with
special training in seizure recognition and testing.  During times when a technician was not
available, EEG recording, video recording, and computer analysis continued, and nursing performed
seizure testing and electrode maintenance.





The Gotman spike and seizure detection computer program (trademark named "Stellate") was used
to screen the EEG in real time for electrographic seizures and interictal discharges.  Samples of EEG
were recorded periodically.  Detections were reviewed in detail by attending neurologist.  All events
and detections, as well as selected samples, were stored to external hard drive media.

head "no." Sways back and forth with eyes closed and appears to be nauseas. She then develops
flexion-extension movements of trunk with side to side head shaking. She is able to remain seated in
the chair. Tech is able to suppress the movements with palpation. Eyes are open and fluttering.
Within 45-60 seconds shaking becomes more irregular and less violent. She does not follow
commands. She continues to have irregular low amplitude body jerks for several minutes after the
violent shaking has stopped. By 12:34 she attends and responds verbally. She cannot remember the
code word.



EEG: No EEG changes from background, aside from movement artifact, were seen preceding or
following the part of the episode that involve violent shaking. Violent shaking has only electrode
movement artifact as correlate.

SUMMARY OF VIDEO EEG FINDINGS:



INTERICTAL FINDINGS:  The patients interictal findings were normal, with a posterior dominant
rhythm consisting of low voltage fast frequencies, without any focal findings or epileptiform
discharges.



ICTAL FINDINGS:


The patient had 2 clinical events that were representative of her typical habitual events at home.
They were semiologically and electrographically consistent with nonepileptic behavioral events.
Two additional clinical events of  "dizziness with right sided numbness" also had no electrographic
correlate, and also consistent with nonepileptic events.




SEIZURE DIAGNOSIS:

1. Nonepileptic behavioral events



EPILEPSY DIAGNOSIS:

1. Nonepileptic behavioral events



CONCLUSION:

The patient was admitted to the epilepsy monitoring unit for 5 days with continuous video EEG.  This
was an elective EMU monitoring session for characterization of events.



The interictal EEG is normal.








The patient was weaned off Keppra over the course of his admission. As the EEG remained normal
without focal features or epileptiform discharges, the patient was counseled about the diagnosis of
nonepileptic behavioral events and that Keppra is not indicated to treat these.  She is to continue off
Keppra.




We recommend that she to see a psychiatrist or therapist for assessment of underlying
psychopathology and diagnosis.

report:
HISTORY:

This is a 42 y.o. left handed female admitted for continuous video-electroencephalography (VEEG)
monitoring with a history of: paroxysmal events of unclear etiology.




Continuous video EEG is initiated for:  Evaluation of paroxysmal events.



Inpatient continuous EEG monitoring required due to one or more of the following reasons:

- The patient is having medically uncontrolled seizures or clinical events, which poses a significant
mortality and morbidity risk.  Continuous monitoring will aid in diagnosis and determining best
treatment options.  If seizures are left untreated, there is a 10-20% annual morbidity and 2% annual
mortality rate.



- Continuous monitoring is required to capture a sufficient number of clinical events or seizures, while
medication are reduced or provoked, which increases the risk of severe seizures and at risk of seizures
causing injury or status epilepticus;






- The EMU is set up to monitor and record EEGs during seizures and it includes nurses trained to
provide first aid and patient safety during seizures;


- The full hospital team must be present to deal with these medical emergency situations should they
arise, including nurses to document patients exam


(9) there have been 13 reported deaths during various video-EEG monitoring procedures, so this is
not a "low risk" service



CONDITIONS OF THE RECORDING:

A routine 21 channel digital EEG was recorded at the onset of monitoring.  The patient then
underwent continuous CCTV/EEG monitoring using a cable telemetry system.  Scalp electrodes were
placed and secured with collodion according to the 10-20 international electrode system.
Additionally, T1, F9, T9, P9, T2, F10, T10, and P10 electrodes were placed in this patient.
Sphenoidal electrodes were not used in this case.  Impedances were measured and verified to be
below 5 Kohms.  EEG activity was recorded referentially to vertex reference, digitized, and stored to
computer hard drive.  Periods of interest were subsequently reformatted to the montage of interest
and reviewed in detail.






Staff supervision, patient-initiated event buttons and computerized algorithms allowed detection of
epileptiform EEG activity and correlation with behavior.  For approximately 8 hours each day the
patient was attended by an EEG technician.  A neurologist was available in person or on call 24
hours per day.  The patient was monitored via video 24 hours per day by a registered nurse with
special training in seizure recognition and testing.  During times when a technician was not
available, EEG recording, video recording, and computer analysis continued, and nursing performed
seizure testing and electrode maintenance.





The Gotman spike and seizure detection computer program (trademark named "Stellate") was used
to screen the EEG in real time for electrographic seizures and interictal discharges.  Samples of EEG
were recorded periodically.  Detections were reviewed in detail by attending neurologist.  All events
and detections, as well as selected samples, were stored to external hard drive media.

amount of bifrontal beta activity, organized in a normal anterior-to-posterior gradient. Wakefulness is
characterized by a posterior dominant rhythm consisting of low voltage fast frequencies.  Lambda
waves are seen in wakefulness.








During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior
dominant rhythm, and diffuse background slowing are seen.



Sleep is characterized by normal sleep transients, with synchronous and symmetric POSTS, vertex
waves, sleep spindles and K-complexes.



No generalized slowing is present. No focal slowing is present.



EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:

No epileptiform activity is present.



OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):

None



ACTIVATION PROCEDURES: Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed



EVENTS:

The daytime technician told the rounding team that "around 2 am" on 6/15 the patient got out of
bed to use the bathroom and reported dizziness and right sided numbness.  The entire record was
reviewed, end-to-end, with particular attention to arousals from 01:45-03:00.  The patient remained
asleep with normal background.




HEART RATE:


A heart rate in the 80s is captured on a single EKG lead.


IMPRESSION:


This is a normal awake and asleep video EEG. There are no clinical or electrographic events
reported or detected.



CLINICAL CORRELATION:

This is a normal awake and asleep routine EEG. A posterior dominant rhythm consisting of low
voltage fast frequencies can be a normal variant in the adult population.


A normal routine EEG does not support or refute the diagnosis of epilepsy.

POSTICTAL CHANGES:  No change

(2) DATE AND TIME:   6/15/2016 at 11:06

EVENT TYPE: Non-epileptic event


CLINICAL: Patient is lying in bed and appears uncomfortable restless; fidgeting with both hands. She
has a few isolated body jerks. She appears as though she is searching for the event button without
moving her head. She utters a few brief moans. Tech comes into room and asks "are you ok?" Patient
does not answer, but isolated body jerks become more frequent. Tech presses button. Body jerking,
now side-to-side, becomes higher in amplitude. Eyes are closed. Patient does not follow commands.
At 11:10, jerks increase in amplitude to become rhythmic shaking with side-to-side head movements,
which gradually decrease in frequency, become lower in amplitude, and become irregular at offset.
Patient has urinary incontinence and postictal confusion.






EEG: No EEG changes from background, aside from movement artifact, were seen preceding or
following the part of the episode that involve violent shaking. Violent shaking has only electrode
movement artifact as correlate.


DURATION: 6 min 29 sec


POSTICTAL CHANGES:  No change

EKG: heart rate increases from 90 bpm baseline to 120s immediately after shaking resolves

Normal background.

flexion-extension movements of trunk with side to side head shaking. She is able to remain seated in
the chair. Tech is able to suppress the movements with palpation. Eyes are open and fluttering.
Within 45-60 seconds shaking becomes more irregular and less violent. She does not follow
commands. She continues to have irregular low amplitude body jerks for several minutes after the
violent shaking has stopped. By 12:34 she attends and responds verbally. She cannot remember the
code word.



EEG: No EEG changes from background, aside from movement artifact, were seen preceding or
following the part of the episode that involve violent shaking. Violent shaking has only electrode
movement artifact as correlate.

SUMMARY OF VIDEO EEG FINDINGS:



INTERICTAL FINDINGS:  The patients interictal findings were normal, with a posterior dominant
rhythm consisting of low voltage fast frequencies, without any focal findings or epileptiform
discharges.



ICTAL FINDINGS:


The patient had 2 clinical events that were representative of her typical habitual events at home.
They were semiologically and electrographically consistent with nonepileptic behavioral events.
Two additional clinical events of  "dizziness with right sided numbness" also had no electrographic
correlate, and also consistent with nonepileptic events.




SEIZURE DIAGNOSIS:

1. Nonepileptic behavioral events



EPILEPSY DIAGNOSIS:

1. Nonepileptic behavioral events



CONCLUSION:

The patient was admitted to the epilepsy monitoring unit for 5 days with continuous video EEG.  This
was an elective EMU monitoring session for characterization of events.



The interictal EEG is normal.








The patient was weaned off Keppra over the course of his admission. As the EEG remained normal
without focal features or epileptiform discharges, the patient was counseled about the diagnosis of
nonepileptic behavioral events and that Keppra is not indicated to treat these.  She is to continue off
Keppra.




We recommend that she to see a psychiatrist or therapist for assessment of underlying
psychopathology and diagnosis.

report:
HISTORY:

This is a 42 y.o. left handed female admitted for continuous video-electroencephalography (VEEG)
monitoring with a history of: paroxysmal events of unclear etiology.




Continuous video EEG is initiated for:  Evaluation of paroxysmal events.



Inpatient continuous EEG monitoring required due to one or more of the following reasons:

- The patient is having medically uncontrolled seizures or clinical events, which poses a significant
mortality and morbidity risk.  Continuous monitoring will aid in diagnosis and determining best
treatment options.  If seizures are left untreated, there is a 10-20% annual morbidity and 2% annual
mortality rate.



- Continuous monitoring is required to capture a sufficient number of clinical events or seizures, while
medication are reduced or provoked, which increases the risk of severe seizures and at risk of seizures
causing injury or status epilepticus;






- The EMU is set up to monitor and record EEGs during seizures and it includes nurses trained to
provide first aid and patient safety during seizures;


- The full hospital team must be present to deal with these medical emergency situations should they
arise, including nurses to document patients exam


(9) there have been 13 reported deaths during various video-EEG monitoring procedures, so this is
not a "low risk" service



CONDITIONS OF THE RECORDING:

A routine 21 channel digital EEG was recorded at the onset of monitoring.  The patient then
underwent continuous CCTV/EEG monitoring using a cable telemetry system.  Scalp electrodes were
placed and secured with collodion according to the 10-20 international electrode system.
Additionally, T1, F9, T9, P9, T2, F10, T10, and P10 electrodes were placed in this patient.
Sphenoidal electrodes were not used in this case.  Impedances were measured and verified to be
below 5 Kohms.  EEG activity was recorded referentially to vertex reference, digitized, and stored to
computer hard drive.  Periods of interest were subsequently reformatted to the montage of interest
and reviewed in detail.






Staff supervision, patient-initiated event buttons and computerized algorithms allowed detection of
epileptiform EEG activity and correlation with behavior.  For approximately 8 hours each day the
patient was attended by an EEG technician.  A neurologist was available in person or on call 24
hours per day.  The patient was monitored via video 24 hours per day by a registered nurse with
special training in seizure recognition and testing.  During times when a technician was not
available, EEG recording, video recording, and computer analysis continued, and nursing performed
seizure testing and electrode maintenance.





The Gotman spike and seizure detection computer program (trademark named "Stellate") was used
to screen the EEG in real time for electrographic seizures and interictal discharges.  Samples of EEG
were recorded periodically.  Detections were reviewed in detail by attending neurologist.  All events
and detections, as well as selected samples, were stored to external hard drive media.

head "no." Sways back and forth with eyes closed and appears to be nauseas. She then develops
flexion-extension movements of trunk with side to side head shaking. She is able to remain seated in

Within 45-60 seconds shaking becomes more irregular and less violent. She does not follow

INTERICTAL FINDINGS:  The patients interictal findings were normal, with a posterior dominant
rhythm consisting of low voltage fast frequencies, without any focal findings or epileptiform
discharges.



ICTAL FINDINGS:


The patient had 2 clinical events that were representative of her typical habitual events at home.
They were semiologically and electrographically consistent with nonepileptic behavioral events.
Two additional clinical events of  "dizziness with right sided numbness" also had no electrographic
correlate, and also consistent with nonepileptic events.




SEIZURE DIAGNOSIS:

1. Nonepileptic behavioral events



EPILEPSY DIAGNOSIS:

1. Nonepileptic behavioral events



CONCLUSION:

The patient was admitted to the epilepsy monitoring unit for 5 days with continuous video EEG.  This
was an elective EMU monitoring session for characterization of events.



The interictal EEG is normal.








The patient was weaned off Keppra over the course of his admission. As the EEG remained normal
without focal features or epileptiform discharges, the patient was counseled about the diagnosis of
nonepileptic behavioral events and that Keppra is not indicated to treat these.  She is to continue off
Keppra.




We recommend that she to see a psychiatrist or therapist for assessment of underlying
psychopathology and diagnosis.

report:
History:	49 year old woman admitted with right parietal hematoma.
Medications:	Valproic acid
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy, portable
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes, awake,
Description:
There is right to left intrahemispheric asymmetry with slower waveforms over the right.  The
background over the left hemisphere consists of 9.5-10 Hz PDR with preserved AP gradient and
excess polymorphic theta activity.  There is no PDR or AP gradient over the right.  The background
over the right hemisphere consists of polymorphic continuous theta and delta activity, most
pronounced over the temporal region.  Frequent brief (2-5 second) bursts of 100-200uV, 2-4Hz
rhythmic bifrontal slow waves occur throughout the recording, increasing in frequency during
drowsiness.  During brief drowsiness, the alpha rhythm attenuates, and 5-7Hz slow waves appear
No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.
Summary of Findings:
Focal slowing, polymorphic, continuous, moderate, right hemispheric, most pronounced over the
Diffuse slowing, polymorphic, mild
No epileptiform discharges
No stage 2 sleep
FIRDA (frontal intermittent rhythmic delta activity)
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL awake and drowsy 22-minute EEG due to mild diffuse slowing and
continuous focal moderate right hemispheric slowing, most pronounced over the temporal region.
Diffuse slowing is indicative of mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is etiologically nonspecific.
Continuous focal slowing is indicative of a focal cerebral dysfunction, likely structural in etiology.
FIRDA (frontal intermittent rhythmic delta activity) is seen in encephalopathy, increased ICP and
bilateral deep white matter lesions.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not
rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.  These findings were conveyed to the primary team.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is an ABNORMAL awake and drowsy 22-minute EEG due to mild diffuse slowing and
continuous focal moderate right hemispheric slowing, most pronounced over the temporal region

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 23-year-old woman with bipolar disease, limited education, 5 weeks postpartum.  Mother reports abrupt onset of head bobbing, arm shaking, and episodes with loss of consciousness for the past 48 hours.
MEDICATIONS:  None.
INTRODUCTION:  A 30-minute digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient had limited communication skills and a translator was used during the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  As the tracing begins, the patient is awake with a 12 hertz alpha rhythm generous, low voltage, frontal central beta.
In wakefulness and early drowsiness, brief bursts of high amplitude, generalized spike and wave activity were noted.  Some of these seem to begin with a burst of fast activity in the occipital regions with a 3-5 Hz spike and wave complex.  The complexes vary in the frequency, many of them are 3 hertz with a polyspike, but the later spikes in the complex are always consistently slower.  Generally, these are frontally predominant spike and wave complexes and those that occur out of drowsiness do not have this beta buzz prior to the spikes.  The patient is noted to have a subtle head bob and sometimes some movement of her legs during the bursts.  She seems to have clinical symptoms with bursts that are 2 seconds in duration.  The bursts are present in wakefulness and early drowsiness.  Hyperventilation may have increase the duration of the spike and wave and polyspike and wave complexes.  In addition, during hyperventilation, there may be a little bit more fast activity.  The patient was otherwise able to answer questions, before and after the discharges.
Photic stimulation elicited a driving response.  Spike and wave activity was noted with a 21 hertz discharge, but was not prolonged relative to other sections of the record.
Heart rate 72 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to generalized spike and wave activity with bursts of 3-5 Hz frontally predominant spike and wave activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The EEG pattern described above is most compatible with generalized mechanism for epilepsy.  The patient's behavior of the head bobbing and sometimes the leg movements are not outside of normal for a absence seizure.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to generalized spike and wave activity with bursts of 3-5 Hz frontally predominant spike and wave activity.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is diffusely slow with primarily a theta frequency pattern and a glimpse of a 6 Hz posterior dominant rhythm.  Shifting slowing was noted.  Bursts of paroxysmal rhythmic slowing were noted as the patient becomes drowsy.

Heart rate 72 bpm.

Marked background slowing.
FIRDA.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 22-year-old male with single seizure in January, perhaps reactive.  Patient subsequently received tramadol for a fracture and had a tonic-clonic seizure.  The patient was started on carbamazepine and since then, complains of feeling spacey.
INTRODUCTION:  One-hour digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient has received levetiracetam 1000 mg during the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  As the tracing begins, the background EEG is diffusely slow with an 8.7 Hz alpha rhythm, but with excess beta and bursts of theta.  Bursts of frontally predominant spike and wave activity are noted.  In addition, isolated right or left frontal spike and wave discharges are noted.  Some of these demonstrate a prominence in the right hemisphere.  Hyperventilation was performed early in the record and clearly accentuates frontally predominant spike and wave activity.  The spike and wave activity ranges from 3 to 5 hertz in frequency.   Discharges are not sustained with most spike and wave complexes either isolated or occurring in bursts, less than 1.5 seconds duration.
Photic stimulation was performed while the patient was drifting off to sleep.  This spike and wave discharges did not seem to be augmented by the photic stimulation, but as the patient transitions to sleep, there was a higher amplitude, frontally predominant slowing with a bit more slow spike and wave activity.  Levetiracetam was given at approximately 12 p.m. and the EEG was recorded until 12:41.  Following the levetiracetam, by 12:30, there did appear to be a decrease in the spike and wave activity.  The paroxysmal slowing was a little less remarkable and while the EEG remained abnormal with excess theta, the overall pattern was improving.  The alpha rhythm was at 8.3 hertz at conclusion.
Heart rate, slightly irregular at 72 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Initially markedly abnormal background with excess slowing and disorganized pattern, improving towards the close of the record.
Frontally predominant spike and slow wave activity.
Focal spike and slow wave activity with a predominance further on the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG may represent a focal or a secondary generalized mechanism for epilepsy.  There was a small degree of irregularity in the heart rate noted in the final pages of the EEG, which may be evaluated by different mechanisms.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Initially markedly abnormal background with excess slowing and disorganized pattern, improving towards the close of the record. Frontally predominant spike and slow wave activity. Focal spike and slow wave activity with a predominance further on the right.

report:
History: 59 year old woman with a reported first convulsion several days ago.
Medications:	Ativan, Ambien, Zoloft
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Extended, 40-60 min
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
The posterior dominant rhythm consists of 10.5-11 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eye
opening.  There is an expected AP gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.
Diffuse excess beta activity is captured.  Symmetrical sleep architecture consisting of vertex waves,
sleep spindles and K-complexes is captured in the second half of the recording.
Multiple events concerning for focal electrographic seizures are captured in the first half of the
recording.  Clinically, patient has not complaints and able to answer questions correctly, including
able to count during these events.  They last ~ 35-55 seconds.  The onset is not clearly lateralized
for the majority of the events.  They start with P3/P4 broad moderate amplitude sharp waves that
gradually increase in frequency up to 6 Hz and spread to the left posterior temporal region
(example ~12:17 PM).  Some events start with ~ 4 Hz medium amplitude rhythmic right parietal
activity that gradually spreads to the left parietal and left temporal regions (example ~12:35:50 pm).
After hyperventilation, brief bursts (<10 sec) of non-evolving shifting bilateral
posterior 5-6 Hz rhythmic moderate amplitude delta activity are captured.  Once P3 and P4 leads
are exchanged at ~12:46:55 PM, the above activity is no longer present.  A single clear right
posterior temporal sharp wave with aftergoing slow wave is captured early in the recording.
Maximal scalp negativity occurs over the T6 lead.  Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds
with good cooperation, and results in increase of bilateral parietal rhythmic delta activity.  Stepped
photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces symmetric photic driving at multiple
Summary of Findings:
Beta, excessive
Sharp waves, one, right temporal, posterior
Sleep, stage 2
Seizure, frequent, bilateral parietal, 35-55 seconds
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL 48 minute awake and asleep EEG due to presence of multiple suspected
bilateral parietal focal brief (35-55 sec) seizures/ ictal runs.  Of note, these runs disappeared once
P3 and P4 electrodes were exchanged but patient also fell asleep.  Additionally, a single clear
right posterior temporal epileptiform discharge is present.  These findings suggest structural focal
cerebral abnormality over the bilateral parietal, right temporal region.  Since It is possible that
activity seen was artifactual (it disappeared after leads were exchanged), a repeat prolonged EEG
may be of benefit.  These findings were discussed with the ordering physician.  Excessive beta
activity could be secondary to the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.

Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates 
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over 
bilateral frontal regions.  Mild degree of excess polymorphic theta activity is captured.  Patient 
remains awake throughout the study.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.

symmetric background slowing.  Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps)

	Diffuse slowing, polymorphic, mild
	No epileptiform discharges
	No stage 2 sleep

disorganization. These findings are etiologically nonspecific indicators of mild diffuse cerebral 
dysfunction.  No epileptiform discharges are present, but stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If 
clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may provide additional information.

This was a technically satisfactory record and included a single channel of EKG.   DAY 1 (6/20/2016, 00:00 - 6/20/2016, 06:00)  BACKGROUND: The waking background is continuous, symmetric, poorly-organized, reactive. Most of the record consists predominantly of delta with superimposed beta. During stimulation, the background briefly reacts with increased predominance of theta and alpha.  There is no posterior dominant rhythm. Well-formed sleep transients are not seen.  There is moderate to severe generalized slowing.   PAROXSYMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):  None  EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:  1. Frequent (>1/min to <1/10s) bifrontal spike-and-wave (Fp1, Fp2 maximum, with higher amplitude consistently over Fp2) 2. Occasional left fronto-temporal (T1>F7/T3/Fp1/F3) spike-and-wave 3. Occasional bitemporal (right max) (T2>T1) sharp waves  EVENTS: No clinical or electrographic events reported or detected  EKG: A single lead captured a heart rate in the 90s.  DAY 1 IMPRESSION & CLINICAL CORRELATION: This is an abnormal long term video EEG due to: 1. Moderate to severe generalized slowing and background disorganization, which may at least in part be due to propofol 2. Multifocal epileptiform discharges as above No clinical or electrographic seizures are reported or detected.      -----------------------------------------------------------------  DAY 2 (6/20/2016, 06:00 - 6/20/2016, 16:00)  BACKGROUND:  Patient becomes more awake beginning around 6/20 07:20. Wakefulness consists of low voltage fast frequency background with excess theta and delta frequencies. Posterior dominant rhythm consists of low voltage fast frequencies. Patient is extubated around this time.  During drowsiness, bursts of rhythmic delta are seen. Sleep not yet captured on this day.  Study is disconnected at 6/20 14:16. At 6/20 14:41 only leads over left hemisphere are reconnected.  GENERALIZED SLOWING: mild  FOCAL SLOWING: None  PAROXSYMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM): None  SPORADIC EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY: None  EVENTS: No clinical or electrographic events reported or detected  EKG: A single EKG lead captured a heart rate in the 80s.   DAY 2 IMPRESSION & CLINICAL CORRELATION  Improvement in degree of background slowing from moderate-to-severe to mild. Epileptiform discharges not seen during this day, which mostly consists of wakefulness.      -----------------------------------------------------------------  FINAL IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal video EEG due to:  1. Moderate to severe generalized slowing and background disorganization, improving to mild generalized slowing by day 2 2. Multifocal epileptiform discharges, seen on day 1 and resolving during wakeful state during day 2:     a) Frequent (>1/min to <1/10s) bifrontal spike-and-wave (Fp1, Fp2 maximum, with higher amplitude consistently over Fp2)     b) Occasional left fronto-temporal (T1>F7/T3/Fp1/F3) spike-and-wave     c) Occasional bitemporal (right max) (T2>T1) sharp waves   FINAL CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These findings indicate the presence of multifocal epileptogenic discharges superimposed on diffuse cerebral dysfunction. The cerebral dysfunction is at least in part related to propofol and may also be indicative of a postictal state that has improved by day 2.
